<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Two bombs exploded at a bus stand near the
historic site of Red Fort in the Indian capital on Sunday evening,
the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The bombs exploded in the congested Walled City area at 20:45
hours Sunday night, the PTI quoted local fire brigade sources as
saying, giving no further details. (India-Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Indonesia will extend full help to Pakistan for
acquisition of the membership of ASEAN and the Asian Regional
Forum, Pakistan's Foreign Office Spokesman Iftikhar Murshad said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting the two-day visit of Indonesian President
Abdurrahman Wahid to Pakistan from June 16-17. (Pakistan-ASEAN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin and his
Eritrea counterpart, Haile Woldensae, signed a peace agreement in
Algiers on Sunday to end their two-year-old border war.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal calls for an immediate truce and the deployment
of a U.N. peacekeeping force in a 25-kilometer buffer zone in
Eritrea until the border between the two countries is demarcated.
(Ethiopia-Eritrea-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Fourteen people, including an army major, two
police officers and 10 militants, were killed in separate
incidents in Jammu and Kashmir since Saturday night, the Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a major encounter, government troops challenged a group of
heavily armed militants trying to sneak into India in Poonch
district in west Kashmir, and in the ensuing exchange of fire an
army major and six militants were killed, the PTI quoted official
sources as saying. (India-Kashmir)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- In a step to spur economic reforms, Jordanian King
Abdullah on Sunday named leading parliamentarian Ali Abu Ragheb as
new prime minister to succeed Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh, informed
sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The lame duck prime minister was seen meeting with foreign
visitors Sunday morning, but Ali Abu Ragheb, 54, may take over as
early as Sunday evening, or at most in a couple of days, the
sources said. (Jordan-Prime Minister) 
</P>
</TEXT>
