<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Refuses to Approve Israeli Withdrawal Complete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Resisting pressure from the United
States, Lebanese President Emile Lahoud on Sunday again refused to
approve that Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon is complete.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese National News Agency reported Lahoud said in a
statement released Sunday that "Lebanon will not lose its hard-
earned victory with resistance and sacrifice after just several
hours of talking."
</P>
<P>
Lahoud made the statement after U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright made intensified efforts earlier in the day to
try to convince Lebanon to accept a U.N. Security Council statement
that could indicate Israel has completed its 22-year occupation of
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that Israelis are still on Lebanese
territory in several border areas and Lebanon objects to the U.N.
line of withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon insists on its position not to give its approval until
its team, together with the U.N. team, verifies the complete
withdrawal on the border, Lahoud was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will regard the Israeli withdrawal as incomplete and
will not accept any false line as an alternative to its
internationally recognized borders, Lahoud added.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud met with the ambassadors of five permanent members of the
Security Council in Beirut on Sunday, asking them to convey the
Lebanese position and requesting support from their governments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lebanon asked the 15 member states of the Security
Council to put off their meeting until it could check to ensure
Israeli forces are gone, local media said.
</P>
<P>
Most members did not want to give Lebanon more time to verify
the border line, whereas Russia backed Lebanon's stance.
</P>
<P>
The dispute has delayed the deployment and reinforcement of the
U.N. peacekeeping force and impeded the Lebanese army to fill into
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan is scheduled to arrive here Monday from Cairo. He will
talk with Lebanese leaders on verifying Israeli withdrawal and
reinforcing the peacekeeping force in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
