<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Upbeats for Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting European Union (EU) Middle
East peace envoy Mieguel Muratinos on Sunday expressed optimism
over the Middle East peace process, saying he expects breakthroughs
in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference in Amman, Muratinos said he believes the
Middle East is more closer than ever to a solution to the decades-
old Arab-Israeli conflicts.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not mention the fact the Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators failed to make substantial progress in their final
status talks after their resumption earlier this month in
Washington, and the Syrian-Israeli talks remains deadlocked since
they broke off in January.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes there will be solutions that will satisfy
all parties in the following weeks which he described as crucial,
and he believes the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations are serious
and all parties remain committed to peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The envoy described as fruitful and constructive his talks
during his one-day visit with King Abdullah and Jordanian officials
over ways of promoting the peace process in the region as well
consolidating bilateral cooperation between Jordan and the 15-
member EU.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU and Jordan share similar stands in supporting the
rights of Palestinian refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
Currently the kingdom is hosting over 1.2 million Palestinian
refugees who fled their homeland during successive Middle East
wars, most of them having been granted Jordanian citizenship. But
Jordan supports their rights of either returning home or asking for
compensations from parties concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
