<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq-Japan Inaugurates Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eight Japanese companies, mostly of technology, pharmaceuticals
and multimedia, were listed on Nasdaq-Japan during the opening
ceremony, NASD Chairman and CEO Frank Zarb said in Tokyo, viewed
here at a televised press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq-Japan is operated in partnership with the Osaka
Securities Exchange, a 51-year-old securities exchange which
recently introduced a fully-automated computerized trading system.
</P>
<P>
Nasdaq-Japan President and CEO Tatsuyuki Saeki expects the
average listed companies to number 10 per month, but Zarb
emphasized the need to develop high quality companies instead of
pursuing the listing number.
</P>
<P>
Zarb believed that the opening of Nasdaq-Japan sets the stage
for a common technology platform linking Asia with Europe and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
In its three-phase development strategy, Nasdaq-Japan uses its
current technology and maintains the standards of order-driven
market functions.
</P>
<P>
In 2001, the market is going to operate its own market
structure and bring together firm quotations and market orders
into an integrated electronic system.
</P>
<P>
And finally, after Phase 2, the market will start cross-border
trading forming a link to Nasdaq Europe, with 24-hour electronic
and internet-based trading expected.
</P>
<P>
Nasdaq, established in 1971, is a fast growing stock market
with close to 5,000 companies listed. The world's largest
electronic market has been striving to expand its business
overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
