<HEADLINE> At least 73 Structures Destroyed in U.S. Wildfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By midday Monday, one of the fires, about 60 kilometers
southwest of Denver, had burned 4,200 hectares of forest and
destroyed 51 houses scattered through subdivisions built into the
steep mountainside.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted local officials as saying that there was a
chance a wind could help fire crews by driving what remains of the
blaze into an area already burned by a 1996 fire, halting its
advance.
</P>
<P>
The second fire, the 4,240-hectare Bobcat Gulch blaze east of
Rocky Mountain National Park about 80 kilometers northwest of
Denver, had destroyed 22 structures, which include houses and
other buildings.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the latest weather forecast, officials at that fire
still hoped to contain it on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,600 firefighters continued to battle both fires,
building fire lines while other crews built terraces on steep
hillsides to prevent erosion.
</P>
</TEXT>
