<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Confident in Curbing Political Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean police said Monday that
certain measures have been taken to ensure the situation will not
run out of control in the run-up to the parliamentary elections
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Police Spokesman Chief Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena told the
Zimbabwe News Agency that police officers had been deployed in
areas where violence was anticipated across the country.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are satisfied with the measures we have put in
place, although we can not cover every corner of the country."
</P>
<P>
"Police reaction groups and members of the Support Unit branch
are on standby in all provinces to deal with political violence,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said police officers would be deployed at all polling
stations later this week ahead of the election.
</P>
<P>
Electoral Supervisory Commissioner Elaine Raftophulous said
political parties should refrain from engaging in violence.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interest of the nation that this election is
conducted in a peaceful manner," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
