<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Cabinet Ratifies Border Agreement with Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Saudi cabinet on Monday ratified
the permanent treaty on international land and sea borders with
Yemen signed on a week ago, which ended their long-running
territorial dispute.
</P>
<P>
The official Saudi News Agency reported this was done in a
cabinet meeting Monday afternoon in Jeddah, a Red Sea port city.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Foad al-Farsi said after the cabinet
meeting that King Fahd had expressed appreciation for the treaty
which he said would be conducive to promoting the friendly and
brotherly ties between the two countries and the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The king praised the treaty as an ideal pattern of joint work
between neighbors in terms of resolving such issues, al-Farsi said,
adding that the monarch expressed hope that it would enhance
comprehensive cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Consultative Council, or parliament, approved the treaty
on Sunday. The king is expected to give an official endorsement to
the treaty before it goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Yemen, with a 2,500-kilometer common border,
had been locked in a territorial dispute, which in 1998 flared up
into a border conflict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the information minister praised the just concluded
ceasefire deal between Ethiopia and Eritrea to end their two-year-
long border dispute as a step towards re-establishing peace and
stability and stepping up development in the Horn of Africa region.
</P>
<P>
He also hailed the efforts made by current Chairman of the
Organization of African Unity, Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika, and other parties concerned for the deal.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by the OAU, foreign ministers of Ethiopia and Eritrea
signed the accord Algiers, capital of Algeria, Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had been engaged in a border dispute since May
6, l998 when Eritrean troops invaded and seized some Ethiopian
territories. Fighting renewed last May along their 1,000-kilometer
border, with Ethiopian troops marching into Eritrea beyond disputed
border regions which were at the root of the border war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
