<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Considering Purchasing Water from Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A high level Israeli delegation
arrived in Turkey on Monday to discuss purchasing water from the
Manavgat river near Turkey's Mediterranean port city of Antalya.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Israeli Water Affairs Director Amos
Epstein, was paying the visit in an effort to find a way out of the
severe water shortage crisis in Israel, Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkey offered to sell water to drought-stricken Middle East
countries from the Manavgat. In Antalya, facilities are ready for
exporting 180 million cubic meters of water annually.
</P>
<P>
Israel, Turkey's main regional ally, has shown strong interest
in the project but has yet to take a final decision because of
domestic objections.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his visit, Epstein said that Israel is starving for
water, and "the urgent solution is to import water. It is
inevitable to purchase water from Turkey."
</P>
<P>
The delegation, composed of officials from Israeli Foreign
Ministry, Health Ministry, and the Treasury as well as leading
water experts, will discuss the issue of buying 50 million cubic
meters of water from Turkey annually.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will visit the Manavgat and bargain with Turkish
authorities over the cost. Turkey is asking 23 U.S. cents for one
cubic meter of water.
</P>
<P>
However, water purification and transfer are increasing the cost
to 55-60 cents, similar to that of purifying the sea water.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the reasons that have drawn oppositions in Israel
to purchasing water from abroad, and the government was urged to
use the money to purify sea water by itself.
</P>
<P>
Israel's leading newspaper Jerusalem Post, in an article
published on Sunday, voted against water purchase from Turkey,
claiming that it was an inefficient and expensive way of solving
the water problem.
</P>
<P>
The only solution is to set up purification facilities, it said.
</P>
<P>
Despite this powerful lobby, the visit showed that the Turco-
Israeli talks about water purchase have entered its final stage.
</P>
<P>
The water to be purchased from Turkey is expected to be
transported to Israeli port of Askelon by oil tankers with a
capacity of 250,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said that even if the two sides sign an agreement
during the visit, the water transfer will not start until next year
due to delay by the construction of facilities.
</P>
<P>
Turkey with rich water resources is trying to play a major role
in "water diplomacy" in the Mideast, where experts claimed that
competing for water resources could become a flashpoint in the next
regional war.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been planning to supply fresh water to dry
Middle East countries in a move to boost its relations with Israel
and Muslim nations in the region, saying water can be a means for
an Arab-Israeli rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Jordan, along with many other regional countries,
have been suffering from serious water shortages due to depleting
resources and an acute drought over the past two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
