<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Minister Warns against Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Forestry Minister Nami Cagan
has sounded an alarm about the ever-increasing danger of forest
fire as heat builds up, reported the Anatolia News Agency on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cagan urged people particularly in the Mediterranean, Aegean and
Marmara regions to heighten vigilance against breakout of forest
fires as summer has set in.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 to 30 fires have erupted in these regions due to
carelessness and negligence of people, Cagan said, adding that fire
brigades have found it difficult to extinguish the fires when winds
happened to start blowing.
</P>
<P>
Although technical and administrative measures are being taken
against forest fires, he said, they still need the assistance of
the radio and television in raising awareness of the citizens
living in these three regions against forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Cagan appealed to the local people to use the fire hotline
whenever they detect a cloud of smoke and sparks of fire.
</P>
<P>
He asked the mass media to give more publicity to fire reports
prepared by the ministry's Fire Action Center in their programs and
to repeat the warning by the Forestry Ministry that special
attention must be paid in the period between June 1 and October 1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a total of 15 hectares of forest was burned in a fire
that broke out in Mugla, an Aegean province, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Four helicopters, 18 spraying vehicles and 150 fire brigades
joined forces in a fight against the fire, which was brought under
control after eight hours since its outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Turkey boasts of more forests than most countries in the Middle
East. According to official statistics, a total of 26 percent of
the lands in Turkey are included under the forestry regime. The
total area covered by good quality, productive forests amounts to
13 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
