<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ragheb Sworn in as Jordan's Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's prime minister designate Ali
Abu Ragheb and his cabinet were sworn in on Monday before King
Abdullah Bin Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The 29-member new cabinet, including Ragheb himself and four
low-ranking ministers of state, marked wider representations of
veteran career politicians and young technocrats.
</P>
<P>
As a tradition, Prime Minister Ragheb concurrently holds the
portfolio of defense.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the 23 members of the outgoing cabinet headed by former
Prime Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh kept their portfolios. Among
them are Minister of Foreign Affairs Abdel Ilah Khatib and Minister
of Finance Michel Marto.
</P>
<P>
As required by the constitution, the new government will submit
itself for a confidence vote in the parliament in the coming weeks,
and analysts believe Ragheb will have little difficulties in
winning support from the parliament, given his strong background in
the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb, 54, has been a member of the house since 1993. He had
been heading the economic and financial affairs committee before he
was named prime minister on Sunday King Abdullah who accepted the
resignation of Rawabdeh a bit earlier.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah has the constitutional rights of appointing, dismissing
governments or dissolving the parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The business-and-reform-minded monarch picked up Ragheb in an
apparent bid to speed up economic reforms in the kingdom based on
understanding with the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund
and other major world creditors.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb is expected to inherit part of Rawabdeh's reform
packages, including the measures to trim public expenditures and
budget deficits, privatize key but non-profitable state enterprises
and to pave the way for more foreign investments into the cash-
strapped kingdom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
