<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Release Three Palestinian Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Israeli prison authority Monday
released three Palestinian security prisoners in accordance with
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's order issued earlier.
</P>
<P>
The three prisoners, freed from Israel's Shata and Shikma
prisons, were all sentenced before Israeli courts for their
allegedly involvement in attacks against Israelis, Israeli
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Juma, from Palestinian main-stream Fatah movement,
caused five Israelis injured in a bombing attack in Great Jerusalem
area in 1993, and had been serving an eight-and-a-half-year jail
term since then.
</P>
<P>
Shadi Aziz Ali, from the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestinians, was sent to jail in May 1994 with a 16-year sentence
for his role in an attack wounding two Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Juma and Aziz Ali are both from East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The third released prisoner, Balal Abdel-Karim, was sentenced to
27 years in prison in 1990 for several grenade attacks on Israeli
soldiers and civilians, causing at least 25 Israelis wounded.
</P>
<P>
Barak announced the release as a good-will gesture to the
Palestinians at last Wednesday's security cabinet meeting, citing
the good cooperation with the Palestinians on security matters as
the reason.
</P>
<P>
Media reports claimed that Palestinian security forces arrested
eight Islamic Jihad activists, who are against the Israeli-
Palestinian peace process and reportedly plot terrorist attacks on
Israeli targets, over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
However, the release encountered unexpected rebuff from the
Palestinians, who claimed that the number of released prisoners is
just not acceptable and not conducive to the peace between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Since the peace process began between Israel and the
Palestinians with the signing of the Oslo Accord in 1993, Israel
has freed batches of Palestinian prisoners as confidence-building
measures.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still 1,650 Palestinian security prisoners
remaining in Israeli prisons. The Palestinians have urged Israelis
to release them at once, which was rejected outright by the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Barak is also facing great pressure for the release from
Israel's Terror Victims Association, who earlier asked the prime
minister to suspend the release in order to enable them to appeal
it to Israel's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The powerful lobbyists group said the release is in violation of
Israel's traditional criteria for releasing Palestinian prisoners,
which prohibit releasing Palestinians who had Jewish blood on their
hands, or prisoners who have not served most of their terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
