<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welfare Overhaul Make One Million Lose Medicaid in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A new Study released here
Monday found that welfare overhaul has caused nearly one million
low-income parents lose their Medicaid coverage in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The study, released by Families USA, an advocacy group that
lobbies for universal health coverage, has examined Medicaid
figures in 15 states with most of the uninsured low-income
population, including Texas, Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
A total of 945,880 adults with children had been dropped from
the program from 1996 to 1999, a decline of 27 percent, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
The study accused the states of mismanaging the implementation
of the 1996 welfare reform law and improperly kicking people off
Medicaid once they left welfare.
</P>
<P>
"The basic thrust of welfare is to move people to jobs, but
unfortunately when they do so they are considered to have too much
income for Medicaid," said Ron Pollack, executive director of
Families USA. "So the reward of moving off welfare is getting no
health insurance."
</P>
<P>
The 15 states in the study are those with the largest number of
uninsured poor people and represent 70 percent of all low-income
uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
Medicaid cost an estimated 181 billion dollars in the Untied
States last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
