<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Tax Reform Discussion Deadlocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA MARIA DA FEIRA, Portugal, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The first
day of the European Union summit went into a critical hitch on
Monday when the much-peddled tax reform discussion was deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
With no agreement reached at Sunday's European council of
finance ministers, the discussion was extended into the course of
the two-day summit proper by the heads of state and government of
EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Yet the extended discussion failed again to produce any
agreement though it finished half an hour later than scheduled and
another extra session was scheduled for late Monday.
</P>
<P>
Austria, Britain and Luxembourg were opposed to the tax reform
proposals that requires either direct taxing of cross-border
savings by non-national residents or providing information on bank
accounts to member states whose residents save their money
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Germany has been leading calls for a common withholding tax on
interest earning from savings accounts held in banks anywhere in
the 15-nation union. But the withholding tax idea has later been
dropped by a large majority.
</P>
<P>
All sides, however, agreed that something has to be done about
the cross-border tax dodge via which citizens in one EU member
state can earn interest on savings in another member state without
paying taxes, resulting in billions in loss of tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
Some nations supported allowing a choice between a 20-percent
withholding tax or sharing information on foreign money savers.
</P>
<P>
But Britain opposed to the tax reform proposals as it saw the
proposals as a potential threat to the Eurobond market based in
the City of London.
</P>
<P>
Austria and Luxembourg opposed to the idea of information
exchange as the two nations have a tradition of banking secrecy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
