<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Remains Largest Debtor to United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Monday
reported that the United States remains the largest debtor to the
world body by owing 1.8 billion U.S. dollars in back dues.
</P>
<P>
What Washington owes the U.N. accounts for two-thirds of the
total due, which has been plunging the United Nations into a
lengthy financial crisis. The U.S. debt includes more than 460
million dollars for the regular budget and just more than 1.3
billion dollars for peacekeeping and international tribunals.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, a nonprofit body, fully relies on
contributions from Member States. The assessment, which includes U.
N. regular budget, peacekeeping and international tribunals, is
made in accordance to a country's share of its Gross National
Product in the world's total.
</P>
<P>
As of May 31, Members States owe the United more than 2.9
billion dollars for current and pass assessments -- 2 billion
dollars for peacekeeping, 821 billion dollars for the regular U.N.
budget, and 83 million for international tribunals.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, in order to deal with the recurrent
regular budget cash deficits, has been periodically forced to
borrow from peacekeeping funds. As a result, the Organization is
unable to reimburse promptly those countries that provide troops
and equipment to peacekeeping operations. At the end of 1999, the
United Nations owed 72 countries a total of 800 million dollars
for troops and equipment.
</P>
<P>
However, on the opposite side, more Member States are paying
their regular budget assessments in full each year -- 126
countries had paid up at the end of 1999, compared with 75 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Under Article 19 of the U.N. Charter, if at the beginning of
the year a country owes the same or more than its total gross
assessments for the previous years, it automatically loses its
right to vote in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The United States saved its face by paying just enough by the
end of 1999 to secure its right to vote at the General Assembly,
but its level of unpaid assessments remains high at nearly 1.8
billion dollars at the end of May this year.
</P>
<P>
The United States is repeatedly under fire at the United
Nations for its reluctance to pay its back dues in full, on time
and with conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
