<HEADLINE> 22 Killed in Traffic Accidents in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A total of 22 people were killed
and 300 others injured in traffic accidents around Greece between
Friday and Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A total of 230 traffic accidents were recorded since Friday,
police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Greece's traffic accident rate is among the highest in the 15-
member European Union (EU) countries, with nearly 3,000 people
killed and 30,000 others injured annually in accidents.
</P>
<P>
Police attribute the high accident rate mainly to Greeks'
aggressive-driving, drunk-driving and careless driving.
</P>
<P>
To reduce traffic accidents in the country, Greece has since
Thursday launched a campaign to bolster the traffic police and
monitor the dangerous stretches of the major national highways,
such as Athens-Thessaloniki highway and Athens-Corinth highway.
</P>
<P>
The surveillance radar at four sites along the highways went
into effect as of Thursday and other measures included the
installation of extensive monitoring equipment and granting
greater autonomy to regional police headquarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
