<HEADLINE> Dutroux Sentenced to 5 Years in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Marc Dutroux had been in prison since August 1996 for abusing
and killing four little girls but he escaped from jail in April
1998 when being escorted to a local court for pre-trial hearings.
</P>
<P>
He broke loose from two armed police officers and snatched a
pistol from one of the police escorts and then grabbed a car
parked outside the local court at Neufchateau in southeastern
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, France and Germany
mobilized more than 5,000 police and gendarmerie in the ensuing
manhunt that took three and a half hours before a forest police
patrol caught Dutroux not far away from Neufchateau.
</P>
<P>
The escape attempt was considered so scandalous that two
government ministers resigned to take the responsibility. The
incident triggered off a loud outcry due to a public perception
that the police had bungled the original investigation into the
disappearance of little girls.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was accused of being at the center of a child sex ring
and the trial of his case is not expected to start before next
year.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Dutroux was found guilty of threatening behavior and
theft. Attempt to escape from prison itself is not a crime in
Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
