<HEADLINE> Experts Urge Access of Poor Africans to Essential Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Medical experts have
proposed a parallel importation of drugs and a compulsory
licensing system to enable poor people in Africa to have access to
essential drugs, Tanzanian newspapers reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The experts at a conference in the Kenyan capital Nairobi
argued over the weekend that current international regulations in
regard to drugs importation or production tend to bar poor
countries from access to essential drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The causes of high prices of medicines in Africa included
strong patent protection, high tariffs, taxes and lack of generic
competition," Professor Carlos Correa, an intellectual property
expert, told the representatives of the East African countries
attending the conference on the Campaign for Access to Essential
Drugs organized by Medicines Sans Frontieres and Health Action
International.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that compulsory licensing would enable
governments to issue licenses to national producers without the
permission of the patent- holders.
</P>
<P>
This would make prices of medicines drop by about 75 percent,
they said, adding that with parallel importation, buyers would be
allowed to purchase the cheapest patented medicines.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), essential
drugs are those that satisfy the health care needs of the majority
of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
