<HEADLINE> S. African Parliament Passes Taxation Laws Amendment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The South African National
Assembly Monday unanimously passed the complex Taxation Laws
Amendment Bill, which includes tax cuts of 9.9 billion rands (
about 1.45 billion U.S. dollars) and measures to tax
foreign-sources dividends.
</P>
<P>
The bill was described as the most comprehensive tax reform
legislation in 30 years, the South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
It will be submitted to the National Council of Provinces for
approval.
</P>
<P>
The bill and particularly measures to tax foreign-sourced
dividends came under fire during public hearings last month, and
were described by private sector tax experts as "draconian".
</P>
<P>
The bill also includes proposals to grant "public benefit
organizations" tax-exempt status, reduce company tax rates for
small businesses, and introduce a 100 rands (about 15 U.S.
dollars) departure tax on international air travel from November
1.
</P>
<P>
Legislation on the shift to a residence-based taxation system
is expected to come before Parliament later this year, and
proposals to tax capital gains earlier in the new year. 
