<HEADLINE> U.S. Formally Ease Sanctions on DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government on Monday
formally eased its half-century economic sanctions on the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The move, which implements an announcement by President Bill
Clinton last September to relax sanctions on DPRK, will allow DPRK
to export raw materials and goods to the United States and open
air and shipping routes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, restrictions on the sale of sensitive duel-use high
technologies and U.S. opposition to loans to DPRK from global
financial institutions will remain in place, according to related
regulations posted in the official publication of Federal Register
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said last week that Washington would soon
announce concrete measures to formally ease sanctions on DPRK
after leaders of DPRK and South Korea held a historic summit in
Pyongyang and agreed to take steps toward reconciliation. 
