<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Restructure State-Owned Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will restructure
three state- owned banks soon in a bid to make them profitable,
local newspapers reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Bank of Tanzania (BoT) as saying in its
latest Monetary Policy statement that it is about to complete
studies for restructuring the Tanzania Investment Bank, Tanzania
Postal Bank and the People's Bank of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring program is aimed at building a sound banking
system in the country in line with the BoT Act of 1995, the
central bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to BoT, it has facilitated the sale of 51 percent of
the shares of the Trust Bank of Tanzania Limited to Driscoll
Investments Limited.
</P>
<P>
"The new owners changed the bank's name to Delphis Bank
(Tanzania) Limited in a strategy to boost depositor confidence
after separating itself from the Trust Bank (Kenya) Ltd.," BoT
said.
</P>
<P>
It said the Greenland Bank (Tanzania) Ltd. would soon be handed
over to the Deposit Insurance Fund for liquidation.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to rescue the bank by finding a buyer ended in vain,
therefore BoT instituted measures to pay depositors and terminate
staff," the central bank explained.
</P>
<P>
It further added that almost all depositors and staff have been
paid and the remaining depositors will have their accounts
transferred to BoT where they would continue to be paid.
</P>
<P>
The central bank disclosed that during 2000/2001 financial
year, it would continue to strengthen its supervisor capacity and
improve on the reporting standards of the commercial banks to
minimize systemic failures.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, Tanzania sold its biggest commercial bank,
the National Bank of Commerce (1997) Limited, to the Amalgamated
Banks of South Africa Group (ABSA).
</P>
<P>
ABSA bought 700,000 shares, equivalent to 70 percent of the
bank's value, leaving 300,000 shares or 30 percent to the
Tanzanian government.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania admitted its failure to operate the bank profitably,
hoping it would be successful after the privatization which
started in November 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
