<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Submits Answers to IOC Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, Switzerland, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Beijing submitted
its answers to the 22 questions raised by the International
Olympic Committee (IOC) here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the main hall of the IOC headquarters today, Secretary
General of the Beijing 2008 Olympic Games Bid Committee Wang Wei
presented 50 documents containing Beijing's preliminary plan to
host the Olympic Games to IOC Sports Director Gilbert Felli and
Head for the IOC's Candidate Cities Relations Jacqueline Barret.
</P>
<P>
At Felli's proposal, the Chinese delegation took some pictures
together with the IOC officials in the hall and in front of the
IOC building to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
After briefing the Chinese delegation about the new procedure,
Ms Barret said that the IOC would send a fax to the Beijing 2008
Olympic Games Bid Committee to confirm the IOC has received
Beijing's answers in one or two days.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is one of the ten cities bidding for the 29th Olympiad
in 2008. The others include Bangkok, Cairo, Havana, Istanbul,
Kuala Lumpur, Osaka, Paris, Seville and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The cities have to submit their answers by June 20, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Through the questionnaire, the IOC will assess each city's
capacity to organize the Olympic Games, the world's largest
sporting event. The IOC administration will collect the completed
questionnaires, analyze them and report to the IOC Executive Board,
who will meet on August 28-29 to make a final decision as to which
applicants will be accepted as bid cities. The announcement will
be made by August 31.
</P>
<P>
"The new procedure is a concrete evidence that our reforms are
in place and working. The rules and procedures are clear and
transparent. This benefits both the cities and the IOC," said
Francois Carrard, IOC director general, on February 24 when the
IOC distributed the questionnaire to the applicant cities.
</P>
<P>
"Bidding to host the Olympic Games requires a major commitment
by each city and its National Olympic Committee," said Felli on
the same occasion. "Today we did two things to help. We
highlighted several areas the cities need to focus on early in the
process, and we gave the IOC a mechanism by which to measure each
city's capacity to host the Olympic Games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
