<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rejects Allegations of Intrusion in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Monday rejected Indian
allegations that thousands of Muslim militants are preparing to
cross into the India-controlled part of Kashmir from the Pakistani
side.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan military spokesman Major General Rashid Qureshi also
denied that his country is supporting separatist Muslim movements
in India-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here, Qureshi called the Indian
allegations rubbish. He said the move is part of India's
propaganda campaign to portray the 11-year old uprising in Indian
Kashmir as Pakistan-inspired rather than an indigenous revolt.
</P>
<P>
"Every time they have a problem inside India-held Kashmir,the
Indians ... always want to externalize it and put the blame on
Pakistan," the spokesman charged.
</P>
<P>
He further said India might be preparing for some adventurism
on the Line of Control (LoC) of Kashmir under the cover of such
allegations. He said Pakistani troops are alert and necessary
measures have been taken to meet any such eventuality.
</P>
<P>
According to Pakistani media reports, military authorities in
India said more than 2,000 Kashmir separatists are waiting to
infiltrate Indian territory from Pakistan-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
India said the militants are spread out at different locations
along the 720-kilometer Line of Control that divides Kashmir
between the two arch rivals
</P>
<P>
Last summer large-scale fighting was triggered along the LoC
after thousands of Muslim militants infiltrated India-controlled
Kashmir and occupied some strategic positions.
</P>
<P>
The disputed Himalayan region has caused two of the three full-
fledged wars between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In the two-thirds of Kashmir under New Delhi's control,Muslim
militants have been combating the Indian troops for the past years.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi accused Islamabad of arming Kashmiri insurgents, but
Islamabad maintains that it only provides diplomatic and moral
support to what it calls Kashmiri freedom fighters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
