<HEADLINE> Indian President Approves IT Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Indian President K. R. Narayanan
Monday gave his assent to the Information Technology Bill, which
aims to facilitate e-commerce through legal recognition of
electronic contracts and prevent computer crimes, the Press Trust
of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Information Technology Bill, which was cleared by the
Indian cabinet on May 13 and approved by both houses of the
parliament shortly after, helped India rank among the world's
first 12 countries with a cyber law.
</P>
<P>
According to the PTI, the Indian president also approved four
other bills adopted during this year's parliament session which
just ended last month. The four bills are the Constitution (81st
amendment) Bill, the Cotton Textile Cess (Repeal) Act, the Direct
Tax Laws Repeal Act and the Major Port Trusts Amendment Bill.
</P>
