<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romtelecom to Invest 6.1 Billion U.S. Dollars in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian national telephone
company, Romtelecom, will invest 6.1 billion U.S. dollars in the
country's rural areas this year in order to extend the public
telephony system, the local Romania Libera Daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to an investment project, Romtelecom will install 3,
700 pay phones in localities with more than 1,000 inhabitants and
725 pay phones in localities with more than 500 inhabitants. At
the same time, the network in urban areas will be extended by 3,
400 pay phones.
</P>
<P>
Besides these, 400 pay phones with booth for handicapped
persons will be installed in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Romtelecom was privatized in November 1998 through the purchase
of 35 percent stake by OTE, a Greek national telephony operator.
Under the contract, OTE would gain the usufruct right over another
16 percent of Romtelecom shares in five years, which ensures its
control over the company.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released under the European Survey
of Information Society about communications and information
technology in Central and Eastern Europe, Romania had no more than
20 telephone lines per 100 inhabitants in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
