<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Court Refuses to Release Frozen Russian Bank Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Tribunal of Grand Investigation
of Paris on Monday rejected a request by the Russian government to
release the 180 million U.S. dollars of Russian bank accounts
France has frozen since May 18.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal said that the Russian government failed to make
proper judicial procedure.
</P>
<P>
France applied a decision by a Swedish tribunal of arbitration
to freeze the bank accounts of 70 Russian government organs, after
a Swiss company, Noga, accused Russia of failing to pay for the
food products it sent to Russia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Noga claimed that Russia owed it 800 million U.S. dollars and
asked for an immediate payment of 63 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The French judicial authorities have frozen the accounts in the
Eurobank of the Russian embassy in Paris, the Russian commercial
representation in France and the Russian representation in the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
