<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Entry Into Euro Zone Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FEIRA, Portugal, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Greece became the 12th
member of the European Union's single currency mechanism after the
EU summit on Monday gave the final approval for its entry.
</P>
<P>
On January 1 next year, the euro is set to replace the Greek
currency of drachma to end the run of a 2,500-year-old currency.
</P>
<P>
EU heads of state and government, who are meeting in the
northern Portuguese resort, approved the Greek entry bid which has
been studied and assessed by the EU council of finance and foreign
ministers respectively.
</P>
<P>
"Greece will be more European with the euro," said Greek
central bank official Emmanuel Emmanuel, "let the drachma remain
in history. What's more important is the stability that the euro
has to offer."
</P>
<P>
Monday's final approval more than rewarded Greece for its years
of belt-tightening to reduce inflation, deficit and public debt as
against government budgets.
</P>
<P>
Greece's state mint has been planning to print euros later this
year, way ahead of the January 1, 2002 -- the target date when
euro will formally enter circulation in all the euro zone
countries that also include Austria, Belgium, France, Italy, the
Netherlands, Luxembourg, Ireland, Spain, Portugal, Germany and
Finland.
</P>
<P>
Greece, the poorest country within the 15-nation bloc, failed
to qualify two years ago for the initial group of euro countries
although more than 70 percent of the Greek population supported
the Greek joining the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Drachma was believed to be the first international currency.
After first minted about 650 B.C. in what is now western Turkey,
the currency was widely used among different city-states in the
ancient world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
