<HEADLINE> EU Decides to Set up Crisis Management Police Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FEIRA, Portugal, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Monday approved the creation of a special police force to be ready
by 2003 for future crisis management operations.
</P>
<P>
The approval was made by the two-day EU summit of heads of
state and government from the 15 member states.
</P>
<P>
With the creation of such a police force, at least 1,000
policemen and women will have to be ready for deployment within 30
days of notice inside Europe.
</P>
<P>
The special police force will be a supplement to the rapid
reaction force to be set up by 2003 by the EU in an attempt to
enhance the capability of crisis management.
</P>
<P>
The EU is to set up a rapid reaction force of 50,000 to 60,000
troops by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been making efforts to improve its crisis management
capability and a rapid reaction force by five nations was first
set up in 1996 as the core of what has become known as the
European Security and Defense Identity (ESDI).
</P>
<P>
The EU has been cooperating with the Western European Union and
NATO to enhance its ESDI and NATO has promised to allow EU to use
its existing but non-commit assets in future peacekeeping
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
