<HEADLINE> Iran Stresses Peaceful Solution to Regional Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
on Monday urged the countries in the Persian Gulf region to resolve
their problems "through negotiations and goodwill."
</P>
<P>
Iran believes that no problem in the region cannot be resolved
through negotiations and goodwill, Khatami told visiting Qatari
Minister of Finance, Economy and Trade Yussef Hussein Kamal.
</P>
<P>
The president explained that the Gulf states are inter-related
in maintaining security and they therefore should explore common
status in the modern world on the basis of mutual respect, mutual
interests and non-interference in each other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has long been against foreign presence in the strategic
region rich in energy resources, insisting that the Gulf belong to
regional nations and their future generations.
</P>
<P>
As chairman of the Organization of the Islamic Conference since
1997, Iran will hand over the post to Qatar at the ninth OIC summit
due in December in Doha. Khatami said Iran has held good
negotiations with Qatari officials on conveying its experience to
them.
</P>
<P>
On the bilateral front, Khatami said there are extensive grounds
for boosting economic, scientific and technical cooperation. He
called for the activation of a Tehran-Doha joint economic
commission.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari minister arrived here on Sunday. He told Khatami that
Qatar attaches special importance to its relations with Iran and
expressed hope that Gulf states would strengthen cooperation to
bring about peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
He has held talks with Iran's First Vice President Hassan Habibi
and Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on bilateral relations and
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been steadily improving relations with its Gulf
neighbors since President Khatami took office in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
