<HEADLINE> Colombia, Iran Join Group-15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 15 (G-15) developing
countries on Monday accepted Columbia and Iran as new members, thus
expanding the group to cover 19 countries.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the group made the decision at the first working
session of the 10th summit opened here earlier Monday, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters following the session.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the leaders unanimously endorsed the two countries'
request for membership, in recognition of their role in the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, founded in 1989 to boost South-South cooperation,
actually has 17 members. They are Algeria, Argentina, Brazil,
Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Kenya, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico,
Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri Lanka, Venezuela and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The member states of the group account for one third of the
world's population and produce 2 trillion U.S. dollars in goods.
Their combined exports last year stood at 361.4 billion dollars and
imports at 357.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting ends on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
