<HEADLINE> Philippine Unemployment Rate Hits 9-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' unemployment rate
reached a nine-year high of 13.9 percent in April 2000, due mainly
to a drop in jobs generated by the agriculture and industry
sectors,the government said Monday.
</P>
<P>
National Statistics Office (NSO) data shows that April's
unemployment rate was the highest since the 14.4 percent rate in
April 1991. The employed numbered only 28.3 million, down by 4
percent from 29.5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
Only the services sector posted an increase in employment with
a 3.2-percent growth and contributed the biggest increment of 291,
000, the NSO said.
</P>
<P>
According to the NSO, the agriculture sector's drop was a
dramatic 12.7 percent in agriculture itself, fishery and forestry.
Industry also registered a 1.3-percent decline.
</P>
<P>
The NSO said the drop in employment in industry was due to
decreases in the sectors of manufacturing, construction and
electricity, gas and water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
