<HEADLINE> Canadian Doctors Warn of "Superbug" Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Canadian doctors are warning of an
era of drug-resistant "superbugs" killing an increasing number of
children in the country, said the Globe and Mail newspaper on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a new Canadian study, the paper said only 2.5 percent of
the infections nationwide turned out to be superbugs in 1991, but
the number had jumped to 13 percent by 1998.
</P>
<P>
Penicillin-resistant bacteria are showing up in one in eight
children affected by life-threatening strains of meningitis,
pneumonia and blood infections, it said. 
