<HEADLINE> Danube Traffic Severely Impaired by Yugoslav Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The freight transport on the
Danube River in the first five months of the year has dwindled by
almost 95 percent from the 1990 level due to conflicts in the
region, the local Curentul daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the corresponding periods, the Danube freight
transport in the first five months of this year was below 10
percent of the figure for 1997 and at around 5 percent of the
volume for 1990.
</P>
<P>
What is more, the traffic was limited to goods carried between
Romanian ports, the paper cited sources of the Romanian River Port
Administration as saying.
</P>
<P>
With poor freight transport, port operators and shippers will
not be able to pay their debts to the River Port Administration
which, in turn, is unable to implement its program of improving
port infrastructures in Romania.
</P>
<P>
The administration is aimed at modernizing the river port of
Cernavoda in eastern Romania this year.
</P>
<P>
During NATO's war against Yugoslavia last year several bridges
over the Danube were destroyed, blocking the waterway and caused
heavy economic loss to the countries along the river. Traffic was
also affected  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
