<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Lifting of Sanctions Unthinkable: Austrian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FEIRA, Portugal, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior Austrian official
said on Monday that no lifting of sanctions against Austria at the
European Union summit was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Finance Minister Karl-Heinz Grasser told the press
after the European council of finance ministers from the EU member
states failed to strike an accord on the proposed tax reformation.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It was unthinkable for Austria's EU partners not to
lift the sanctions imposed on my country."
</P>
<P>
He said that even the people of the EU member states have been
appealing for the lifting of the sanctions imposed after the
Austrian coalition government incorporating the far-right Freedom
Party was swore in on February 4.
</P>
<P>
A recent EU-wide survey found that most of the respondents were
in favor of normalizing bilateral relations between Austria and
its EU member states.
</P>
<P>
"Why not use open discussions to find a solution toward the
issue of sanctions," said the finance minister who added that he
was confident that a final solution would be found in that there
was no legal basis for the current sanctions established by the 14
other EU member states to protest against the incorporation of
Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party in the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
"No base at all," said Grasser, "so I am confident that an
agreement will be reached in the end on lifting the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
Austria has become a tricky problem for the two-day EU summit
of heads of state and government by becoming a ball that has been
kicked around by Portugal, which is holding the rotating
presidency of the 15-nation bloc, the EU member states and the
European Commission, the executive body of the EU.
</P>
<P>
All seemed to have been shunning the responsibility of
initiating to lift the sanctions that have no legal base in the
European Union treaty. Portugal said that it was the decision by
all the 14 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The EU commission said that the issue was not at the EU level
and that it had to be settled at bilateral level.
</P>
<P>
Some member states have been moving toward the lifting of the
sanctions but France and Belgium, the hardliners in the matter,
still opposed to the lifting of sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
