<HEADLINE> Beijing, Main Maker of Own Air Pollution: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital should mostly
take the blame for its own air pollution, though deserts in the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and some other areas in the
country are the main cause of the 10 severe dust storms that hit
the city this spring.
</P>
<P>
This was the judgment of Song Xiyou, head of the Capital
Afforestation Committee and director of the Municipal Forestry
Bureau. He was speaking here today at the launching ceremony of
international company Unilever's tree-planting program. Unilever
is pouring seven million yuan into the program.
</P>
<P>
Song revealed that 80 percent of pollutants in the atmosphere
at the higher level above the city comes from outside, while 80
percent of pollutants in the air at the lower altitude are
produced locally. This shows that the problem of air pollution
remains critical, he said.
</P>
<P>
The city government attaches great importance to the issue, and
so far its urban afforestation plan, known as "Covering up the
Yellow Soil," has been completed by planting trees and covering
pavements with concrete bricks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
