<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Nations Urged for Common Ground in Facing Globalization  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries must work
together to forge a unified stance in facing the challenges of
globalization which has proven harmful to the world's poorest
nations.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made here Monday at the opening session of the
10th summit meeting of the Group of 15 (G-15) developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inaugural session of the two-day summit meeting,
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said globalization should lead to
improving standards of living in developing countries, however, "
imbalance in the world economy is increasing instead of
decreasing."
</P>
<P>
The developing nations are concerned with the developments of
globalization because the average growth rates in the developing
countries have decreased from six percent to two percent since the
1997 Asian financial crisis, Mubarak told leaders of the G-15 at
his presidential palace in northern Cairo.
</P>
<P>
To cushion the negative effects of globalization, Mubarak said,
developing nations should enhance their cooperation with
international partners to build a new world economic order based
on "equality, justice and democracy."
</P>
<P>
Echoing Mubarak's worries about globalization of free trade,
Jamaican Prime Minister Percival James Patterson said at the
opening session that globalization may be proven a challenge to
developing nations in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization requires greater, not less, global governance. It
demands greater and more genuine democratic governance. This may
turn out to be our greatest singe challenge," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he acknowledged that globalization does have one
positive effect, which has brought people around the world closer
together.
</P>
<P>
"We must draw strength from this precious unity," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo said in his speech on
behalf of G-15 members from Africa that developing countries are
overwhelmed by the "strident" consequences of globalization, which
caused the collapse of commodity prices, "a mockery" of efforts to
raise output.
</P>
<P>
He also renewed appeals by summit participants to the West, such
as the G-8 industrialized countries, for helping release the burden
of billions of dollars in debt, which has hindered their efforts to
build modern economies.
</P>
<P>
The two-day G-15 summit was held one month before the meeting of
the G-8 industrialized nations in Japan in July. And Mubarak will
contact the G-18 leadership to convey the G-15 position once it is
adopted.
</P>
<P>
The president called on the developed countries to write off
some 350 billion dollars in African debts which required African
countries to set aside some 40 percent of their budgets.
</P>
<P>
Nations of the G-15, which has grown to 17, account for one
third of the world's population and produce 2 trillion U.S. dollars
in goods. Their combined exports last year stood at 361.4 billion
dollars and imports at 357.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, founded in 1989 to boost South-South cooperation,
groups Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia,
Kenya, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri
Lanka, Venezuela and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Monday's summit meeting also coincided with the tenth
anniversary of the founding of the group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0114 </DOCNO>
