<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Asks U.N. to End Israel's Continuous Occupation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
said here on Monday Lebanon wants U.N. peacekeeping force to end
Israel's continuous occupation on some parts of the Lebanese-
Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
Speaking prior to meeting U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
Hoss also said Lebanon holds the continuation of the Israeli
violation of the international border represents a violation
threatening the safety and sovereignty of Lebanese territories that
must not be allowed by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council decided on Sunday to certify Israel
has ended its 22-year occupation of south Lebanon despite Lebanese
complaint that about 13 areas are under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
"U.N. peacekeeping must be responsible for removing the Israeli
violation on the international border immediately", Hoss added.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in Beirut Airport after he arrived Monday noon that "
the U.N. has not been demarcating the border between Lebanon and
Israel and between Lebanon and Syria, but it is necessary for the
U.N. to mark a withdrawal line on the ground, the so-called blue
line."
</P>
<P>
He admitted both Israel and Lebanon have their problems with the
withdrawal line, but the line is not the border and should be
respected by both sides.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general pointed out that Israel has withdrawn its
troops from Lebanon in line with Resolution 425 and verifying
Israeli withdrawal is his responsibility with a "neutral and
impartial manner".
</P>
<P>
As for the alleged Israeli violation on Lebanese border, Annan
said "it is another matter".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan stressed that "if the Lebanese government
believes that there has been violation of the withdrawal line,
there should be immediately report of the matter to the United
Nations. Since the line has been established, any cross of the line
is a violation."
</P>
<P>
Annan also expressed the hope that the Lebanese government will
deploy its army in the south and reassert its authority there.
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud said on Sunday Lebanon will not
approve the council's statement until Lebanese teams and U.N.
peacekeepers will have verified the withdrawal is complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
