<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Army Denies Reports of Encounter With Indian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh army Monday refuted
news reports of any encounter with Indian separatist rebels in
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) in the northeastern part of the
country, which borders India, official Bangladesh News Agency
reported here.
</P>
<P>
"This report is not true. We did not have any encounter with
Indian rebels in CHT, particularly after the 1998 peace accord,"
an army spokesman in Chittagong told the national news agency.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, a senior army official, however, admitted that
they often carried out jungle operations to track down Indian
rebels on the basis of allegations from India or local information,
but "we have not encountered or traced any such elements recently.
"
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has said repeatedly over the past several years that
it would not allow its territory to be used against any country.
</P>
<P>
A foreign news agency Sunday reported that Bangladesh soldiers
killed 11 Indian separatist rebels belonging to the outlawed
National Liberation Front of Tripura (NLFT) as they were hiding in
the remote Sajec area in CHT.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified Indian intelligence sources, the report
said Bangladesh troops attacked an NLFT base camp early this week
when at least two to three top leaders of the group were killed.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Rifles officials in Dhaka said they were not
involved or aware of any such encounter either.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the NLFT, two other major outlawed separatist groups,
the United Liberation Front of Assam and the National Democratic
Front of Bodoland, are active in northeastern India bordering
Bangladesh,earlier reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
