<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fear for Sharia Prompts Exodus in Northern Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people have been
fleeing Kano and Kaduna, two of Nigeria's northern states, for
fear of another scourge over the implementation of the Islamic law
Sharia, as an earlier one in February in Kaduna had killed nearly
1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The Muslims in Kano had reportedly threatened a showdown if the
Sharia did not come into force on Wednesday as promised by state
governor Rabiu Kwankwaso last week, Lagos-based newspaper reported
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some Christians in the two states have also vowed
that the implementation of Sharia would mean disaster to the
country. They accused the Muslims of using the law to drive them
out.
</P>
<P>
To forestall possible violence, police in the states have
beefed up their patrols, while an army unit stationed near Kaduna
warned last week that it would take "violent" actions to crack
down on trouble-makers.
</P>
<P>
Kano and Kaduna are two most popular and influential states in
the northern part of Nigeria. Unlike other northern states, which
are dominated by Muslim population, the two states have a large
Christian population.
</P>
<P>
Two other northern states, Zamfara and Sokoto, have already
introduced Sharia into their criminal code earlier in the year
despite the opposition from the Christian dominated southern
states and the federal government.
</P>
<P>
Sharia, mainly implemented in Islamic countries, is a code of
living for Muslims. Apart from its religious contents, the code is
known for its regulations that women must cover themselves and
different sexes must be segregated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
