<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Tax, Austria Overshadows EU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FEIRA, Portugal, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of European Union
(EU) countries Monday began a two-day summit in the Portuguese
resort of Feira, which is expected to be overshadowed by a debate
on a uniform interest tax plan and sanctions against Austria.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers from the 15-member bloc held a special
meeting before the summit to try to strike a deal on Portugal's
proposal that EU members unify their policy on savings interest
tax, which should not be below 20 percent of the savings interest.
</P>
<P>
Cross-border tax dodge costs EU countries billions of dollars
as citizens of one country may earn tax-free interest on savings
in another.
</P>
<P>
No deal was reached at the finance ministers' meeting and
Portuguese Finance Minister Joaquim Pina Moura has vowed to push
for the proposal during the summit.
</P>
<P>
Although the question of Austria was not on the agenda of the
summit, Vienna is expected to raise the issue in its fresh bid to
get rid of the sanctions imposed by its 14 partners after the
formation of its new government incorporating the far-right
Freedom Party in February.
</P>
<P>
France, which will take over the EU's rotating presidency on
July 1, has made clear that it would not take up the issue during
its six-month presidency. However, some other EU countries are
eager to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Other topics of the summit include the enlargement of the EU to
take in Eastern European countries, the EU's institutional reform,
a common foreign and defense policy, and relations between Europe
and Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the interest tax and Austria issues will
cast a shadow over the discussion of these topics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
