<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Firemen Killed in Helicopter Crash in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Five firemen were killed Monday in
the crash of a fire department helicopter in the foothills of the
Apennines mountain, 40 kilometers east of Rome.
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred while the firemen were searching for a man
and his nine-year-old son, who were reportedly missing, on Mount
Gennaro between the towns of Vicovaro and Rocca Giovine, the
Italian news agency Ansa quoted local police as saying.
</P>
<P>
The father and the son, on a weekend camping trip, were found
Monday morning by the police and said to be in good condition.
</P>
<P>
The crashed B-412 Drago 56 helicopter, which lifted off from
Rome's Ciampino airport, went down after its rear rotor ran into a
high tension line rising over rough terrain.
</P>
<P>
The pilot, co-pilot and three specialists on board were all
staff of the national fire department with more than five years'
experience in their job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
