<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Vice President Al Gore Tuesday will detail a new plan
that allows American workers to build up retirement savings
through new investment accounts -- a proposal that on the surface
appears strikingly similar to the central concept of the Social
Security plan offered by his Republican rival, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
-- Ethiopia and Eritrea pledged Sunday to end a two-year-old
war that has led to the deaths of tens of thousands of soldiers
and civilians, and invited a U.N. peacekeeping force to monitor
their disputed 960-kilometer desert border.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The strange case of lost and found nuclear secrets at U.S.
Los Alamos National Laboratory look on a political edge Sunday, as
some Republican leaders in Congress called on Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson to resign after yet another security lapse at the
New Mexico laboratory.
</P>
<P>
-- The governing Baath Party of Syria Sunday unanimously
elected Bashar al-Assad, the son and heir apparent to the late
President Hafez al-Assad, as its secretary general, on the second
day of a crucial party congress.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- A classified report prepared by a U.S. Pentagon-appointed
panel raises further concerns about whether the schedule for
developing a national missile defense shield is realistic and
whether the system will be able to distinguish enemy warheads from
decoys.
</P>
<P>
-- The European Commission is forging ahead with plans to
unleash the cross-border investment potential of the European
Union's various national pension funds, which together manage
about 2 trillion U.S. dollars in assets. 
</P>
