<HEADLINE> Paper Urges Medical Reform in Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- People's Daily, the leading
newspaper in China, will publish a commentary Tuesday calling for
speedier reforms of the medical care system in cities and
townships.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the State Council issued a directive on the
reform issue, jointly written by eight central government
departments.
</P>
<P>
It says that the reform, together with the establishment of a
basic medical insurance system for urban employees, is aimed at
building up an urban medical care system up to the requirements of
the socialist market economy, boosting the healthy development of
the medical and pharmaceutical industry, and enabling the people
to enjoy fair-priced and quality medical services.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper criticizes the poor services offered by some
hospitals in urban areas, their waste of resources, generally poor
financial performance, disorder in the production and marketing of
medicine, lack of a competitiveness among public hospitals, and
skyrocketing medical costs.
</P>
<P>
The commentary urges to introduce a mechanism for competition
into hospitals and drug stores; separate government departments in
charge of the sector from medical care institutions; allow the
setting-up of hospitals in various forms; and bring the production
and marketing of medicine back to order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
