<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches Two Venture Capital Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday launched two
venture capital funds to finance high technology venture projects.
</P>
<P>
The two new funds amounting to 300 million ringgit (78.94
million U.S. dollars) are contributed by Bank Negara (State Bank)
Malaysia (BNM) and Mayban Venture Capital Company (MVCC) and
Commerce Technology Ventures (CTV).
</P>
<P>
BNM allocates 100 million ringgit (26.31 million dollars)each
in both MVCC of Maybank and CTV of Bumiputra Commerce Bank (BCB)
while Maybank and BCB invest 50 million ringgit (13.15 million
dollars) respectively in MVCC and CTV.
</P>
<P>
The funds form part of the 500 million ringgit (131.57 million
dollars) fund which is contributed by the government and the
private sector as announced by the government in Budget 2000 to
fund hi-tech venture projects.
</P>
<P>
The two new funds will help promote entrepreneurs and firms
engaged in the hi-tech sector of the Internet and
telecommunications, life sciences and advanced manufacturing,
Maybank Chairman Mohamed Basir Ahmad said at the launching.
</P>
<P>
The funds also consider firms that meet requirements to become
Multimedia Super Corridor companies and those that could be listed
on the Malaysian Exchange of Securities Dealing and Automated
Quotation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that with an average investment of 3 million ringgit (
780,000 dollars) in each company, it was hoped that CTV and MVCC
could assist at least 100 hi-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
According to official data, the venture capital industry has
grown at an encouraging rate with venture capital companies
reaching 37 with assets of over 1.5 billion ringgit (390 million
dollars)to date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
