<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Aluminium Smelter Casts First Ingot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambique Aluminium Fabricator
(MOZAL), located at Beluluane on the outskirts of Maputo, took
another step towards full production on Sunday when it cast its
first aluminium ingot, said a press release reaching here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, which was made available in London by
one of the major shareholders in the smelter, the British company
Billiton, the first aluminium was produced 25 months after work on
the smelter began, and six months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
"The production of MOZAL's first aluminium, under budget and
ahead of schedule, is a remarkable engineering and managerial
achievement, and testimony to the technical capacity and
investment merits of southern Africa," said Billiton chairman
Brian Gilbertson in the release.
</P>
<P>
"It was always our hope that MOZAL, and its unique public and
private sector partnership, would be a powerful catalyst for
economic development in the region," Gilbertson said.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the project thus far, and the benefits that
have already begun to flow from it, have reaffirmed this hope. The
partners of MOZAL now look forward to a safe and successful
ramp-up of production to the smelter' s 250,000 tons per annum
capacity," the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
The production of metal ingots indicates that MOZAL has started
 commission its 288 reduction cells -- the furnaces in which
aluminium is produced from alumina through electrolysis.
</P>
<P>
"Activity will now focus on completing the remaining facilities
and on conducting trials and tests," the MOZAL release said,
adding that production will be raised gradually until it reaches
the 250,000 tons per year figure in the first quarter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
The smelter is expected to be officially inaugurated sometime
later in September and be fully put into production in 2001. All
the raw materials will be imported from Australia and the United
Kingdom while the products will be exported to Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
MOZAL, a project kicked off in July of 1998, boasts of an
investment of about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars. The largest
stakeholder is South Africa accounting for 43 percent of the
share, followed by the United Kingdom for 23 percent, while the
rest capital came from Japan and the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
