<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seeks Emergency Water Imports From Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A high-level "emergency panel" of
Israeli water experts and government officials is to leave for
Turkey on Monday to discuss possible import of Turkish water.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the present state of water resources, importing
water from Turkey this summer appear an unavoidable solution," the
Israeli daily Ha'aretz quoted a member of the delegation as saying.
</P>
<P>
The panel is to meet officials of the Turkish national water
company to assess the possibility of importing 50 million cubic
meters of water in an initial phase.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli national water company, Mekorot, warned on Sunday
that by fall, Israel's three main reservoirs, namely the Kinneret
(the Sea of Galilee), the mountain reservoir and the coastal
reservoir, would drop to "unprecedented low levels."
</P>
<P>
Under current proposals, says the Ha'aretz, Turkish water would
be transported in old, specially converted 250,000-ton oil tankers.
The tankers are to be discharged at a terminal to be built in
Ashkelon, in southern Israel. The water would then be piped to a
reservoir to be part of Mekorot's national water system.
</P>
<P>
The system, which would also require laying a 13-kilometer
pipeline, would cost an estimated 20 million U.S. dollars. The
imported water itself would cost about 65-75 cents per cubic meter.
But experts said that imported water is comparatively cheaper than
desalinized water.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said there are serious potential problems facing
the nation's aquifers. There has been a gradual decline since 1994
in the output of the Banyas and Dan springs in the northern part of
the country, and in the levels of water wells in the mountain
regions.
</P>
<P>
The continued drop in rainfall throughout Israel has also caused
an average drop of one meter per year in the level of the Dead Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
