<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Earthquake Rocks Northern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake with moderate
strengthen rocked the Northern Philippines Monday afternoon and it
was strongly felt in the capital city of Manila, but no damages
were expected.
</P>
<P>
According to a preliminary report issued by the Philippine
Institute of Volcanology and Seismology, the quake measured 5.6 on
the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter was 26 kilometers northwest of Nasugbu, Batangas,
on the Luzon Island, it said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake occurred at 17:34 local time (09:34 GMT) and
lasted less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
The institute put the intensity in Manila and Tagaytay City at
IV.
</P>
<P>
It said that no damages were likely, but aftershocks were
expected.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, a quake with a magnitude of 5.7 hit the
northern city of San Fernando, the Luzon Island.
</P>
<P>
No casualties and damages were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is hit by an average of six earthquakes every
day but most are too weak to be felt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
