<HEADLINE> DPRK Urges Japan to Take Actions for Bilateral Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) on Monday urged Japan to take concrete moves to
push forward the talks between the two countries, the Korean
Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After the historic summit between the leaders of DPRK and South
Korea, Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori has more than once
said "Japan has strong will and eagerness to improve the relations
with DPRK," said a commentary published by the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Some senior Japanese officials also formally expressed the
similar ideas such as "the chance is ripe" for the two countries
to hold talks.
</P>
<P>
DPRK always keeps the door of talks with Japan open, said the
commentary.
</P>
<P>
"If the Japanese authorities have a sincere and strong will for
improved (DPRK)-Japan relations, there is no need for them to
hesitate over the issue," the commentary added.
</P>
<P>
It has always been the stance and attitude of DPRK to sincerely
hold talks with Japan and improve the bilateral ties on the basis
of conforming to the interests of two peoples, said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
DPRK and Japan held a first round of high-level talks in
Pyongyang in April, marking a resumption of normalization
negotiations that collapsed in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
