<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Euro Zone Inflation Rates Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA MARIA DA FEIRA, Portugal, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The average
inflation rates for both the European Union and the euro zone
remained stable between April and May, Eurostat reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical office of the European
Community said that the annual inflation rate for the 15-nation
bloc stayed at 1.7 percent while that for the 11-nation euro zone
remained at 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Twelve months ago, the average inflation rate was 1.1 percent
for the European Union and 1.0 percent for the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
Ireland registered the highest inflation of 5.1 percent,
followed by Spain at 3.2 percent while Britain posted the lowest
inflation rate at 0.5 percent, followed by Sweden at 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with April 1999, the annual inflation rate rose in 10
of the 15 EU member states and fell in five. The biggest relative
rise was found in Sweden where inflation rose from 0.3 percent to
1.3 percent in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The European Union set 2.0 percent as the ceiling for the 15-
nation bloc and the rise of the inflation in the past year was
mainly attributed to the fall of the exchange rate of the single
currency to the United States dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
