<HEADLINE> Turkey Intensifies Contacts With Iraqi Kurds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkey, afraid of an independent
Kurdish state in northern Iraq, is increasing its contacts with
Iraqi Kurdish oppositions for a reconciliation between Iraqi Kurds
and the Baghdad administration, local media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a recent visit to Baghdad, Turkish Foreign Ministry
Undersecretary Faruk Logoglu suggested that the Iraqi authorities
attach importance on providing administrative services in the
Kurdish-populated northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been plagued by the Abdullah Ocalan-led Kurdistan
Workers Party (PKK), which had waged a 15-year armed campaign
against Ankara since 1984 demanding Kurdish self-rule in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
However, after his arrest in February, 1999, Abdullah Ocalan has
called on his followers to lay down arms and make peace with
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkey expects to play a role in promoting the reconciliation in
Iraq due to its close relations with Iraqi Kurdish oppositions,
including the Massoud Barzani-led Kurdistan Democratic Party and
the Jalal Talabani-led Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that leaders of all Iraqi opposition groups,
including Iraqi Kurds, will go to Washington to meet U.S. Vice
President Al Gore next week. The United States has been seeking to
topple the Iraqi regime of Saddam Hussein. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
