<HEADLINE> Internet Users to Double in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The number of internet users in
Kenya will double in the next two months with the implementation
of the Kenya Education Network in August.
</P>
<P>
The People daily newspaper Monday quoted Director Jason Githeko
of the African Virtual University Center as saying that the number
of internet users in the East African country will rise from the
current 50,000 to 100, 000 countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Githeko told a recent information technology exhibition held in
the capital Nairobi that the education network to be run by high
learning institutions and research organizations will mainly
target students and rural folks within the research and learning
circles.
</P>
<P>
The program, which will be e-commerce oriented, is designed to
equip participants with the latest knowledge on the world markets,
Githeko said.
</P>
<P>
The network, sponsored by the U.S. government at a cost of
300,000 U.S. dollars, has already been implemented by other
African countries like Rwanda, Uganda and Ghana.
</P>
<P>
"Up to 23 institutions in Kenya will benefit from the program,
including all public and private universities, and two teacher
training colleges among others," Githeko said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
