<HEADLINE> EU Ready to Recognize Palestinian State: Israeli Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
getting ready to recognize a Palestinian state if one is declared
in September, whether by agreement with Israel or unilaterally,
local daily Ha'aretz reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A special committee of EU officials is currently discussing the
status of the European consulates in Jerusalem after the EU
recognizes a Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital, the
paper added.
</P>
<P>
In the Berlin Declaration of March 1999, the EU expressed
support to the founding of an independent Palestinian state in the
territories and called on Israel to conclude final-status
negotiations with the Palestinians within one year.
</P>
<P>
In turn for Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's willingness to
postpone the declaration of an independent Palestinian state in the
territories, set for May 1999, most of the EU countries promised to
recognize a Palestinian state even if Israel and the Palestinian
side failed to reach agreement by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
United States officials denied that the Berlin Declaration had
been coordinated with it, but American sources have said the
declaration was preceded by a favorable nod from Washington, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry fears that France's assumption of the
rotating EU presidency at the beginning of July will further
promote the Palestinian efforts to invoke the Berlin Declaration.
</P>
<P>
It did not escape Israeli attention that President Jacques
Chirac was the only Western leader to attend Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad's funeral last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
