<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli government is considering the possible handover
of the Jerusalem suburbs of Abu Dis and Ayzaria to full Palestinian
control on Friday, when the third West Bank redeployment under the
interim accords is to take place.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said Sunday that the move may be aimed at
calming the atmosphere for U.S. special peace envoy Dennis Ross'
expected arrival on Thursday, and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's arrival either by the weekend or next week.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Knesset (parliament) last month endorsed to transfer
of three Arab villages outside Jerusalem to the Palestinian control
as an "advance payment" prior to the third deployment. The move was
frozen by Prime Minister Ehud Barak in protest against the violence
on the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- After the announcement Sunday night that the Israeli
government would meet this week, it seems unlikely that Barak would
postpone, yet again, Tuesday's cabinet meeting in an effort to buy
more time and avoid an eruption of the crisis with the ultra-
orthodox Shas party.
</P>
<P>
Shas insisted Sunday that they would not support any further
postponements and warned that if no agreement is reached by Monday,
their ministers would resign.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to Barak said that if the prime minister believes
that more time is necessary for negotiations between his One Israel
party and Shas, he will opt to postpone the meeting. Barak delayed
the cabinet meeting from Sunday to Tuesday in a bid to settle the
coalition crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- A serious water shortage is likely to force Israel to order
emergency water shipments from Turkey this summer, Mekorot water
utility chief Amos Epstein said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A top-level inter-ministerial delegation is to leave for Turkey
on Monday to examine water sources and discuss possible timetables
for delivery of imported water.
</P>
<P>
Mekorot has warned that by fall, Israel's three central
reservoirs would sink to "unprecedented low levels."
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Tens of thousands of settlers are expected to travel to
Jerusalem on Monday with their children as part of a day-long
strike declared by the right-wing Yesha Council of Jewish
Settlements.
</P>
<P>
The protest follows reports that Barak plans to give the
Palestinians over 90 percent of the West Bank territory,
dismantling Jewish settlements in the areas to be handed over, or
leaving them under the Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
Protests in Jerusalem began Sunday with the Samaria local
council busing students to demonstrate outside the prime minister's
home. 
</P>
