<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Urged to Liberate Bonded Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Twenty Nepal-based international
non-governmental organizations (INGOs) appealed the Nepali
government to immediately take measures to liberate the bonded
laborers in the country, a report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a joint appeal issued on Sunday, the INGOs requested the
Nepali government to make provisions in writing for relieving the
bonded laborers of the debts and obligation to their alleged
masters, facilitate compensation to them for their unpaid wages
and provide land for cultivation, the Rising Nepal newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Even 70 years after the abolition of slavery and 10 years
after the restoration of democracy, there are still more than 25,
000 Nepalese citizens enslaved by their owners in bonded labor,"
the appeal said.
</P>
<P>
"Not only does such a practice trap them into a life of
unrelieved poverty, the continued existence of these illegal and
inhumane practices would undermine Nepal's standing in the
international community," it added.
</P>
<P>
Women and children have suffered miserably under this
exploitative system, said the appeal, urging the government to act
positively and immediately to eliminate the existence of bonded
labor practice.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers in Nepal's remote villages are forced into bondage
after borrowing money from landlords and are never able to get out
of it because of their ignorance and illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial estimates put the number of bonded laborers at 40,
000.
</P>
<P>
The 20 INGOs include Handicap International, Swiss Association
for International Cooperation, Save the Children Norway, World
Neighbors among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
