<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Group Postpones Talks with Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front (
MILF), the biggest Muslim rebel group in the southern Philippines,
has postponed its scheduled fifth round of formal talks with the
government on June 28.
</P>
<P>
MILF military affairs chief Al Haj Murad said in a press
statement available Monday that continuous military offensive
against MILF camps in Mindanao and the military attention to
arrest top leaders of the rebel organization were the main reasons
why they are temporarily deferring the said talks.
</P>
<P>
According to Murad, the government has issued arrest warrants
against the three top MILF leaders, namely himself, MILF chairman
Hashim Salamat and MILF political affairs chief Ghadzali Jaafar.
</P>
<P>
Murad added that the time frame given to them by the government
to submit comments on its proposed political package on June 21,
cannot be met on time by them.
</P>
<P>
During the government-MILF fourth round of talks on May 30, the
MILF negotiating panel initially agreed to submit their comment on
June 21.
</P>
<P>
"But it was unanimously decided in a special meeting by the
Majlis As-Shoora, the MILF's parliament, to ask the government
peace panel to defer the said talks," Murad explained.
</P>
<P>
Murad, however, clarified that the MILF is not closing its door
on the ongoing peace talks. He stressed that the peace talks would
determine the political destiny of the Muslim people in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
But Edgardo Batenga, government chief peace negotiator, was
reported as saying that he is yet to receive an official
declaration from the MILF regarding the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
