<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Needs Funds to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's National AIDS Control
Council needs 14 billion shillings (about 184 million U.S.
dollars) in its five-year strategy to combat AIDS, according to
Director of the council Tom Okeyo.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Monday quoted Okeyo as
saying the money for the 2000-2005 period will be used in
awareness campaigns and purchase of drugs and other services.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar for the members of Parliament on AIDS held
here at the weekend, Okeyo said 2 million Kenyans were HIV
positive while another 1. 5 million have died as a result of the
disease since 1984.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, Speaker Francis ole Kaparo of the National
Assembly announced that an AIDS Control Unit has been established
at the Parliament buildings.
</P>
<P>
Retired archbishop Manasses Kuria of Anglican Church of Kenya
said Sunday that deaths among youth in the country are rising due
to the escalating rate of HIV/AIDS infections.
</P>
<P>
Most youth completing school and other learning institutions
die quickly from AIDS, the archbishop added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA, EU Remain Zambia's Major Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Zambia continues to earn over 60
percent of its total exports within the Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) region and the European Union (EU),
the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Export Board of Zambia (EBZ) as saying in its
April 2000 report on the exporter audit 1999 that the country's
overall exports to the EU region had increased by about 10 percent
in the period under review.
</P>
<P>
EU was the largest market for non-traditional exports (NTEs),
accounting for about 38 percent or 117,000 U.S. dollars of the
total NTE earnings.
</P>
<P>
The largest market in the EU region was the Netherlands
accounting for 34.61 percent of the total EU exports. The products
to this market included cut-flowers, live fish and wet-blue
leather, EBZ said.
</P>
<P>
The United Kingdom (UK) was the second largest market in the EU
region, accounting for 31.86 percent, followed by Germany for
18.17 percent. The main items of Zambia's exports to the UK
included speciality vegetables, cotton yarn and cut flowers.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, COMESA was the second largest regional
market for Zambia's exports in the year under review and accounted
for 26.88 percent of the total NTE earnings.
</P>
<P>
The principal export products in 1999 to the region included
sugar, petroleum, maize, fresh eggs, chemicals, asbestos piping,
roofing sheets, electricity, cement and cotton, EBZ said.
</P>
<P>
It said South Africa is increasingly becoming an important
market for Zambia's electricity, scrap metal, cotton, soya beans,
gemstones, tobacco and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
However, the report noted that the overall total exports
earnings for 1999 including sugar and cobalt had reduced by 18.14
percent from 1998's 943 million dollars to 772 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decline was attributed to the decline in production and
prices of copper and cobalt, the report said, noting that the
average price of copper had declined by 5.3 percent from 0.75
dollar per pound in 1998 to 0.71 dollar in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Troops Accused of Planting Mines in Kisangani </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Army Spokesman Phinehas
Katirima Monday accused Rwandan army of planting landmines to blow
up the Tchopo bridge in Kisangani, the scene of six days of
clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan troops recently.
</P>
<P>
"The wire connected to the battery that was to be used to
detonate the mines ended up in the Rwandan army defenses,"
Katirima told Xinhua, saying that it is a clear indication of the
Rwandan motives.
</P>
<P>
"Our positions were in north of the bridge and the wires
connecting the landmines to the batteries are south of the bridge
where the Rwandans were," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Observer Mission in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC) has sent experts from Kinshasa to clear the
mines from the bridge and civilians have been stopped from using
it, according to sources here.
</P>
<P>
The situation is a bit complicated now with the entry of a
landmine war into this conflict, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops fought each other at the Tchopo
bridge in Kisangani, a northeast city of the DRC. The six-day
clashes, which started on June 5, killed 150 civilians and wounded
more than 1,000 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
