<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo Following Recent Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo
Monday, led mainly by high-priced information and technology
issues which were boosted by stability in New York's Nasdaq
composite index, with the benchmark Nikkei index turning upward
Monday for the first time in five trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 273.04 points, or 1.67
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 16,591.35.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 25.44 points or 1.69 percent to 1,533.
88.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 610.85 million
shares from last Friday's 653.40 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Akai Electric was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
High-priced information and technology issued drew active
buying while a report that post offices and several major banks
are planning mutual use of each other's automated teller machines
provided investors with an incentive to buy bank issues, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
The glass and ceramics industry was also up, while the
brokerage, rubber and air transportation sectors marked large
gains.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, losers included fishery, agricultural and forestry
issues, wholesalers and pharmaceutical firms.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outpaced
losers 708 to 538, with 153 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
<P>
In Osaka, Nasdaq Japan, Japan's version of the technology-laden
U.S. Nasdaq market, kicked off trading Monday with eight companies,
four of them start-ups, offering new shares to investors.
</P>
<P>
Nasdaq Japan, associated with the Osaka Securities Exchange, is
competing with its two rivals, the Mothers market and the over-the-
counter market, in wooing cash-strapped venture businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
