<HEADLINE> Beijing Opens Government Hotline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Municipal Government
today opened a hotline for citizens to air their complaints about
city services.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Qi, mayor of Beijing, this is part of the
government's efforts to improve its working style so that it can
better tailor its work to meet the needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
Beijing opened a hotline to the mayor's office in 1987, which
received about 350,000 calls every year. The new hotline is based
on that system, an official source said.
</P>
<P>
Huang Chengxiang, secretary-general of the municipal government
of Beijing, said Beijing now has five million telephones, topping
the nation in terms of per capita telephone ownership.
</P>
<P>
"With more citizens making calls to the mayor's hotline, we
need to improve the equipment and expand the crew," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The new service line operates with the most advanced computer
and telecommunication equipment. It has ten operators and 50
automatic service lines, all available for calls 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
The new hotline number, 12345, will also be used as the public'
s direct line to the government in other Chinese cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
