<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC-Japan Trade Up in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The overall trade volume between
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) countries and Japan rose by 4.6
percent in 1999 to 33.2 billion U.S. dollars, reported Monday's
Dubai based daily Gulf News.
</P>
<P>
The hike was mainly attributed to the rise in the price of crude
oil, the major commodity of Japanese imports from Gulf countries,
</P>
<P>
GCC-Japan trade constituted nearly 5 percent of Japan's world
trade in 1999 which amounted to 727.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports to the GCC stood at 7.56 billion dollars in
1999, down by 22.7 percent from 9.78 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Japanese imports from the GCC surged by nearly 17 percent to
over 25.59 billion dollars in 1999, compared to 21.92 billion
dollars in 1998. Mineral fuels, including crude oil, petroleum
products, petroleum gas and other gaseous hydrocarbons, constituted
98 percent of the imports.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia emerged as Japan's largest trading partner among
the GCC in 1999, pushing previous No.1, the United Arab Emirates,
down to the second position. Japan's trade with all GCC countries
rose with the exception of Bahrain - which declined mainly due to a
70-percent fall in Japan's exports.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain is the only GCC country that does not export crude oil
to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, which groups six Gulf Arab countries, namely Saudi
Arabia, the UAE, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman and Kuwait, supplies nearly
71 percent of Japan's crude oil needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
