<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Town May be Transferred Soon: Israeli Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government is
considering carrying out a much postponed decision to transfer an
Arab town near Jerusalem to full Palestinian control later in the
week, Jerusalem Post quoted senior Palestinian sources as reporting
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The town, Abu Dis, may be handed over on Friday when the third
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank is to take place.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian source indicated that the Israeli move may be
aimed at calming the atmosphere for U.S. special peace envoy Dennis
Ross' arrival on Thursday, and preparing the visit to the region by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright by the weekend or next
week.
</P>
<P>
Albright is to seek a way out of the crisis in the Israeli-
Palestinian talks and "the Americans are trying to convince us to
accept a delay of the third withdrawal and there is talk that
Israel may transfer Abu Dis...but no decision has been taken yet,"
the source added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has sought to delay the
redeployment and make it part of a framework accord for a final-
status agreement, but Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat insists that
Israel implement the withdrawal, mandated by the Sharm el Sheikh
peace deal signed last September, before signing a framework
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Prime Minister's Office did not deny that
consideration is being given to handing over Abu Dis, which the
security cabinet decided in principle to do last month.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of Abu Dis has been postponed due to the violent
anti-Israel protests in the West Bank and Gaza Strip last month.
</P>
<P>
Israel would probably withdraw from Abu Dis to give the
impression that it is keeping its part of the bargain, another
Palestinian source said.
</P>
<P>
However, the source added, the gesture is long overdue and the
Palestinian side would continue to insist that Israel withdraw from
all the West Bank, except specified military locations, and land
left for the final-status, like borders, Jerusalem and settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli security cabinet was presented on Sunday with a
gloomy picture of the negotiations with the Palestinians, as high-
level intelligence officials warned of possible future violence in
the West Bank if no progress was made in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak stressed during the cabinet meeting the importance of
holding a summit between himself and Arafat as soon as possible to
try to close the gaps.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he feels the Israeli-Palestinian peace march is
coming to its end and that the hour of real decision-making is
near.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians signed the Oslo accord in 1993,
which underlined the principles for solving the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation to the final-status talks with the
Palestinians, headed by Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami,
returned home on Monday after winding up their week-long talks in
the United States. No substantial progress was made during the
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
