<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish parliament will discuss eight investigation files
this week, of which five are on the ruling partner Motherland Party
leader, Mesut Yilmaz, and one on the opposition True Path Party
leader, Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
The debate will begin on Thursday and be followed by votings. At
least 276 votes are required to send a deputy to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The voting results are crucial for the tripartite coalition
government led by Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish intelligence agency mapped the Islamic fundamentalist
movements, showing where and to what extent the radical
organizations are active over the country.
</P>
<P>
According to a report, prepared by the agency, the
fundamentalist organizations have formed powerful bases in central,
eastern and southeastern Anatolia.
</P>
<P>
Yenibinyil:
</P>
<P>
-- In order to reduce the financial burden of the military
expenditure on the economy, Turkish Armed Forces (TSK) called on
the Foreign Ministry to develop good relations with neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the TSK and the Foreign Ministry had begun
to coordinate their efforts to shape the new foreign policy toward
neighbors, highlighting Ankara's recent efforts to further trade
relations with Iran and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet:
</P>
<P>
-- One of Turkey's famous archaeological sites, the ancient city
of Zeugma, is facing its last days in the light of day as it will
be under water very soon due to flooding from Birecik Dam.
</P>
<P>
A group of archaeologists have been working day and night to
save what they can before the ruins are claimed by the dam's water.
</P>
