<HEADLINE> Australian Diplomat Stands for Lifting Sanctions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian diplomat formerly
in charge of disarming Iraq, Richard Butler, Monday argued that
continued sanctions against Iraq are a failure, but are deeply
harming its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who was head of the United Nations Special Commission
on Iraq (UNSCOM), said the Iraqi population was being hurt deeply
by the decade-old sanctions that no longer had any effect.
</P>
<P>
"They (the sanctions) are today a failure, but because they
still exist today, they are deeply harming 22 million people,"
Butler told the Australian National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
Butler, now a diplomat in residence at the Council of Foreign
Relations in New York, said he had not been able to criticize the
U.N. sanctions until he quit his UNSCOM post early last year.
</P>
<P>
Butler also attacked the U.S. missile defense shield program as
a mistake that would lead to a new way of nuclear weapon
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
"I think this is a disaster," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
