<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy to Grow by 4-4.5 Percent Next Year: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia's Central Bank (Bank
Indonesia) predicted here Monday that the country's economy will
grow by between 4 to 4.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a hearing with the House of Representatives (DPR)
Commission IX on state budget, finance and banking, Governor of
Bank Indonesia Syahril Sabirin said: "We predict that Indonesia's
economy in the year 2001 will grow by between 4 to 4.5 percent in
line with the economic growth in the medium term which is expected
to reach between 5 to 6 percent."
</P>
<P>
He believed that foreign investors' confidence will also
recover next year.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin also estimated that inflation rate in the year 2001
based on consumer price index will stand at the level of 5 to 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
"And the exchange rate of rupiah (Indonesian currency) will
stand at the level of 6,800 to 7,800 rupiah per U.S. dollar in the
year 2001," the governor said.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthening of the rupiah in the year 2001 is due to the
success of corporate debt restructuring program," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin also predicted that crude oil price in the
international market will reach 18 to 19 U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
However, Minister of Finance Bambang Sudibyo predicted earlier
that crude oil price will reach 17 to 22 U.S. dollars per barrel
next year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Sabirin urged the government "to realize the
social and political stability in order to attract foreign
investors back to Indonesia." 
</P>
</TEXT>
