<HEADLINE> Uganda Ready for Court Fight on Reparations for Kisangani War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is ready to go to court if
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) files a case for
reparations following the Friday resolutions by the United Nations
Security Council, the New Vision reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Kinshasa has already taken us to court before. We are waiting
if they will file a fresh application after the Friday
resolutions," Attorney General Bart Katureebe was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council resolved that Uganda and Rwanda should pay
for the loss of life and the property damaged in the Kisangani
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops, based in the eastern part of the
DRC to support rival rebel factions fighting against the DRC
President Laurent Kabila, fought each other in the northeast
Congolese city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
The clashes, which started on June 5 and lasted six days,
killed150 civilians and wounded 1,114 others.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council also voted unanimously for a
resolution ordering all foreign forces to leave the DRC, but did
not set a deadline.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people in the Rwandan capital Kigali on Thursday
demonstrated against U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's proposal
to the Security Council to adopt a resolution calling on Rwanda
and Uganda to withdraw troops from the DRC, said the New Vision.
</P>
<P>
The Kinshasa government last year filed a case against Uganda
and Rwanda in the International Court of Justice in the Hague,
accusing the two countries of plundering its resources and killing
its citizens. Kinshasa asked for reparations and the withdrawal of
both countries' troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
