<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Former Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita died
of respiratory failure at 00:53 local time Monday (1553 GMT Sunday)
at a Tokyo hospital, Kyodo News reported. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita, a member of the House of Representatives for the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), served as Japan's prime
minister from 1987 to 1989. A native of Shimane Prefecture,
western Japan, Takeshita had been elected to the House of
Representatives 14 times. (Japan-Obit-Takeshita)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HELSINKI -- Chairman of the InterAction Council Malcolm Fraser
strongly condemned here Sunday the operation launched in Kosovo by
the U.S.-led NATO last year as an ironical scheme.
</P>
<P>
Fraser, former Australian Prime Minister, made the condemnation
at the opening ceremony of the 18th annual meeting of the
InterAction Council, an organization of former heads of state and
government. He noted that before NATO's military intervention in
Kosovo, a Yugoslav province plagued by ethnic problems, the number
of refugees in the region was only 70,000. But it rose to 1.2
million at the end of the war, and 90 percent of the killed were
civilians. (Helsinki-InterAction Council)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Responding to increasing pressure from outside,
Afghanistan's ruling Taliban have closed down three military
training camps and placed new restrictions on Arabs associated
with Saudi exile Osama bin Laden, a report here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper The News quoted Pakistani officials as saying
that Mullah Abdul Akhund, Taliban's interior minister, ordered the
immediate closure of the camps following his visit to Islamabad in
mid-May. More than 1,300 militants from the banned Harakatul
Mujahideen, a group involved in the movement of the independence
of Kashmir, and many Arabs were ordered to vacate the Riskor
military garrison, 25 kilometers to the south of the Afghan
capital of Kabul. (Pakistan-Taliban-Camps)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Group-15 nations opened their 10th summit in Cairo
on Monday, which was attended by seven presidents, one prime
minister, three vice presidents and senior officials from the 17
member states.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day conference, the participants are expected to
discuss world economic development trends, economic globalization
and its effect on developing countries in particular, elimination
of poverty, reduction of debts, fight against unemployment and
activation of joint projects among the members. While seeking
inter-G-15 economic and trade cooperation, the organization is
expected to forge a common stance calling for a world economic
order that will not limit access of developing countries to the
markets of developed nations. (Egypt-G-15-Summit) 
</P>
