<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dunhuang Studies Need Collaboration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUNHUANG, (Gansu), June 19 (Xinhua) -- A famous Chinese expert
on Dunhuang studies,today stressed the importance of collaboration
in the research on the 100-year-old branch of learning in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, 84-year-old Duan Wenjie,
also honorary president of the Institute of Dunhuang Studies, said
materials and references that are still locked away in archives
will be no good to the development of Dunhuang studies.
</P>
<P>
"Murals, statues and cultural relics in the Sutras Cave at
Dunhuang are perfectly matched and embody the essence of Dunhuang
culture," said Duan, who has devoted more than 50 years to
studying the grottoes at Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
Duan has copied 340 pieces of murals since he graduated from an
art school in 1945 and published a great number of academic papers
and books.
</P>
<P>
In 1900, a Taoist priest, Wang Yuanlu, discovered a cave at
Mogao Grottoes in Dunhuang which contained more than 50,000 sutras,
documents and paintings of nearly 10 dynasties from the 4th to the
11th century. The Mogao Grottoes was included by the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)
onto the World Heritage List in 1987.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 research organizations on Dunhuang Studies have
been built with a dozen universities and institutes in China. The
Institute of Dunhuang Studies located near the site of the
Dunhuang Grottoes, is the largest research organization on
Dunhuang Studies in China. It has 240 research fellows.
</P>
<P>
From July 29 and August 3, China will hold a series of grand
ceremonies in both Beijing and northwest China's Gansu Province to
mark the centenary of the discovery of the Sutras Cave and the
beginning of Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony will be held in Gansu on July 29 to commend Chinese
and foreign individuals, including Duan Wenjie, and research
institutes and organizations which have made outstanding
achievements in Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
"I hope to see in my lifetime more Dunhuang cultural relics
abroad returned to China," said Duan, adding that he also hoped
that a well-equipped museum to be built to house and protect
cultural relics from Dunhuang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Reports Rise in Monthly Retail Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Shanghai amounted
to 13.96 billion yuan in May, a 13.3-percent rise from the same
month in 1999, according to Shanghai Municipal Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The increase is partly due to the week-long Labor Day holiday
and an international garment fair in the city from May 10-18.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows that 139 of the local supermarkets, department
stores, restaurants and food shops brought in 970 million yuan in
sales during the week-long Labor Day vacation starting May 1, a 42.
6 percent climb over the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the June 1 International Children's Day, reading
materials and garments for children, toys and stationery sold
especially well.
</P>
<P>
Local retail sales for food items exceeded 5.2 billion yuan in
May, up over 10 percent on a yearly basis, with the volume for
clothing growing by 25 percent to reach nearly 2.23 billion yuan
and that for daily-use articles rising nearly 10 percent to 6.38
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The local catering sector had 1.08 billion yuan in business
turnover in May, a 28.8-percent rise on a yearly basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
