<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major River in North China Almost Dry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- One of the major rivers in north
China's Shanxi Province has almost run dry due to a prolonged
drought, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the runoff of the Qinhe River is only 0.1 to 0.
2 cubic meters per second now, the lowest in history.
</P>
<P>
The whole river basin has been affected by the drought,
described as the most serious since 1636.
</P>
<P>
The 450-km-long Qinhe River is the source of drinking water for
millions of people. Its normal runoff is 3.14 to 10.82 cubic
meters per second. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
