<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand, Australia to Propose S. Pacific Whale Sanctuary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Conservation Minister Sandra
Lee will lead New Zealand's largest-ever official delegation to
this year's International Whaling Commission (IWC) meeting in
Adelaide, Australia, next month.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government said in its Monday's press release
that during the meeting, New Zealand and Australia will jointly
propose a South Pacific whale sanctuary be established.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed South Pacific whale sanctuary will complement
existing sanctuaries covering the Southern Ocean and the Indian
Ocean," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"It will ensure that southern hemisphere whales are protected
in their South Pacific breeding grounds as well as their Southern
Ocean feeding grounds," she added.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that about 300 delegates and observers from
around 35 countries are expected to attend the IWC's plenary
session in Adelaide, which will run from July 3 to 6.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand and Australian joint proposal will require the
support of a three-quarters majority of voting members to
establish the sanctuary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
