<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Trade Ban Counterproductive: New Zealand FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Foreign Minister
Phil Goff has warned a that a trade ban could entrench a racist
government in Fiji and expose Fijian-Indians to increased violence,
a Wellington-based newspaper, the Evening Post, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Goff has called on New Zealand's Council of Trade Unions (CTU)
to stop plans to impose a trade ban on Fiji, saying the New
Zealand government "can not condone an action that is illegal."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister noted trade bans on Fiji would be
counterproductive and more likely to hurt the people.
</P>
<P>
"The Fijian economy is on the verge of collapse and if it does
many people will lose their livelihoods, both low-income
indigenous Fijians and Indian-Fijians," Goff said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister noted that a trade ban on Fiji would also
jeopardize the economies of Tuvalu and Kirabati. The two island-
states, he added, ship most of their goods through Fiji.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the CTU announced it will impose a seven-day cargo
bans on Fiji from Tuesday. In the announcement CTU President Ross
Wilson called on all New Zealand workers to refuse to handle goods
destined for or received from Fiji at all points of the production
and transport chain.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Goff has spoken to Wilson by phone and they
expect to meet to discuss the issue this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
