<HEADLINE> Laid-off Women Benefit from UN Loans (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chen now has started her own fast food take-out business. The
couple get up at 4:00 or 5:00 a.m. washing vegetables in the
morning and preparing for the next day's food late into the night.
They are satisfied though.
</P>
<P>
Chen said,"We don't have to worry much about money now." She
said the four-member family used to live on 700 yuan every month.
Besides food and daily necessities, the couple have to pay for
their son's tuition and medical charges of their father in his
eighties, who is now paralyzed in bed.
</P>
<P>
By starting her own business, their monthly income has
increased to about 2,000 yuan. "We wish to pay off the debt of
some 30,000 yuan to our relatives this year," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, the loan acceptors have to pay
back the money on 24 terms within one year, with the interest rate
of about 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Guo is satisfied with the progress, saying that the project,
though small in size, is expected to give the Chinese government
some advice on how to help the laid-of workers, women in
particular, during the going-on nationwide campaign to bring many
State-owned enterprises out of debt.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been continuing its efforts to aid
the laid-off people by opening training programs, seeking job
opportunities, distributing unemployment pensions and issuing the
lowest living standard insurance.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Labor and Social Security shows
that 11.74 million people lost jobs last year in the State-owned
enterprises reform, and 4.92 million of them were re-employed
after taking specific skill training programs. 
</P>
