<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Observes Sanitation Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A one-week sanitation campaign
was launched here Monday with the objective to create awareness
regarding personal hygiene among the public and improve sanitation
situations in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Sanitation Action Steering Committee
(NSASC), poor sanitary condition is the root cause of many
infectious diseases in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
A survey issued here Sunday by NSASC said about 28,000 children
die from diarrhea each year and Nepal bears the damage of about 10
billion rupees (144 million U.S. dollars) in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The survey identified lack of toilets, use of uncleaned toilets
and unsafe drinking water as some of the reasons for deaths of
thousands of Nepalese children.
</P>
<P>
It said 80 percent of Nepalese do not use toilets and 80
percent of communicable diseases are caused by unsafe drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
NSASC, one of the organizer of the sanitation campaign, called
on governmental, non-governmental and social organizations to join
hands to accelerate the campaign.
</P>
<P>
During the monsoon season from mid-June to September,
infectious diseases are pervasive in Nepal and claims thousands of
lives each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
