<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Experts Fear Black Buck Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Nepali experts predicted that
black buck is on the verge of extinction if no proper conservation
efforts are made, a report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The population of black bucks, found only in the Terai plain in
mid-western Nepal, has gone down to 42 from 177 in 1989, according
to a recent count of the endangered species conducted by Black
Buck Conservation Center (BBCC) of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Poaching, improper habitat, insufficient drinking water and
frequent attacks by dogs and hyenas lie behind the decline of the
black bucks, said the survey, which was available Monday.
</P>
<P>
The BBCC appealed to governmental and non-governmental
organizations to step up conservation efforts in order to save the
endangered species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
