<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-off Women Benefit from UN Loans (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Chen Meirong, a laid-off woman in
north China's port city of Tianjin, had never given a thought that
she could have connection with the United Nations when she was 48
years old.
</P>
<P>
With the 4,000 yuan (about 480 U.S.dollars) in small loans from
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) six months ago, Chen
has been self-employed after two years' staying at home.
</P>
<P>
Guo Ruixiang, a UNDP official, said the project, carried out by
the All-China Women's Federation (ACWF), is the result of a joint
effort by three parties, UNDP, Australian Agency for International
Development, and the Chinese government. It is expected to use
circulation funds of 900,000 U.S. dollars to help re-employ 1,800
Chinese laid-off women.
</P>
<P>
Ma Jinping, an official with the ACWF Tianjin Branch, said
Tianjin has been selected as China's only experimental city as it
is the largest industrial city in north China. The number of women
layoffs account for 30 percent of some three million laid-of
workers in the municipality, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma, 118 applicants have been chosen in Tianjin so
far, all of whom are between 25 to 50 years old. It is hard for
them to be re-employed due to their low educational level and
scant technical skills. Moreover, it is usually the women in China
to take care of the whole family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Sees No Immediate Threat to Apparel Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The government of Bangladesh held
the view that an immediate threat to the country's apparel export
to the United States is unlikely, the Independent newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was feared that the country's garment exports to the United
States might be badly affected due to the passage of the "Trade
and development Act of 2000" in the U.S. Congress last month
providing easy trade facilities to 48 sub-Saharan African,
Caribbean and Central American states.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a senior official of the Ministry of Commerce
as saying that there might not be an immediate threat to
Bangladesh apparel exports to the United States since only eight
of those 48 countries produce ready-made garments (RMG) while
others are yet to develop infrastructure for such industry.
</P>
<P>
"The total RMG produced by those eight countries are much below
that of ours," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Compared to these countries' combined annual woven and knit
apparel export of 585 million U.S. dollars, Bangladesh's export to
the United States was 1,917 million dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The bill passed in the U.S. Congress allows duty free entry
into the country through September 30, 2006 without any
quantitative limits of textile and apparel articles imported from
sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
Business circle of Bangladesh apprehended that the new
legislation of the United States would hit Bangladeshi garment
export to that country hard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
