<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Close Militant Camps: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Responding to increasing
pressure from outside, Afghanistan's ruling Taliban have closed
down three military training camps and placed new restrictions on
Arabs associated with Saudi exile Osama bin Laden, a report here
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper The News quoted Pakistani officials as saying
that Mullah Abdul Akhund, Taliban's interior minister, ordered the
immediate closure of the camps following his visit to Islamabad in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,300 militants from the banned Harakatul Mujahideen,
a group involved in the movement of the independence of Kashmir,
and many Arabs were ordered to vacate the Riskor military garrison,
25 kilometers to the south of the Afghan capital of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The garrison, once housing the seventh division of the Afghan
army, served as the largest military training camp for radical
Arabs and other groups, The News said.
</P>
<P>
Two other camps, including one at Kargha, some eight kilometers
to the northwest of Kabul and a relatively smaller training
facility, were also ordered to close down.
</P>
<P>
"We have verified now that all the three camps have been closed
down," an anonymous senior Pakistani official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani sources said the Taliban militia had suffered
immensely from international sanctions imposed on Afghanistan last
November for its refusal to hand over Osama bin Laden, who is
suspected of being the mastermind behind the deadly 1998 bombings
of American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Pressure was exerted through Pakistan which faced repeated
calls to use its influence over the Taliban to close down "
terrorist training camps" in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
