<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand will likely record the highest rate of
retail sales growth in Southeast Asia in the second half of this
year, the Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fueled by the economic recovery, retail sales in Thailand are
likely to rise by 15 percent from the same period of last year to
126.5 billion baht (3.24 billion U.S. dollars), Suthichart
Chirathivat, president of the Thailand Retailers' Association, was
quoted as forecasting.
</P>
<P>
He based his forecast on talks with presidents of retailers'
associations in the region, where most consumers are continuing to
restrict their purchases because of economic difficulties. (
Thailand-Retailing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan's Finance Minister Shaukat Aziz said
Sunday the government has decided to deregulate the furnace oil
imports and the prices of Liquid Petroleum Gas (LPG).
</P>
<P>
With this decision the private sector will be allowed to freely
import and distribute furnace oil, he said at the post-budget
press conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said the price of LPG will be deregulated from September
2000 with the commencement of production in the PARCO Refinery
that would add 450 tons of LPG to the existing supplies of 540
tons in the market.
</P>
<P>
With this development Pakistan might be in a position to export
LPG, as the expanded supplies would be more than the local demand.
(Pakistan-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Personal Computer (PC) sales in the Middle East
will continue to grow this year with the expected sale of 100,000
units in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and 330,000 units in Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The PC sales in the region topped the one million mark for the
first time in 1999, a surge from 600,000 two years ago, Sunday's
Dubai based daily Khaleej Times quoted market analysts as saying.
</P>
<P>
The International Data Corporation (IDC) said dynamic consumer
PC sales, a booming portable PC market and Windows 2000 upgrades
are all contributing to the constant boom in PC shipments this
year. (UAE-Computer)
</P>
