<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Denies ILO's Accusation of Forced Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar Monday denied the accusation of the International Labor
Organization (ILO) that there is forced labor in the country,
arguing that it is called "contribution of voluntary labor."
</P>
<P>
The denial came four days after the International Labor
Conference (ILC) passed an unfavorable resolution regarding
Myanmar's labor issue last Wednesday at its 88th session held in
Geneva, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The article emphasized the need not to lose sight of various
aspects, gaps and ownership levels due to the differences existing
between one country and another in trying to accept the
globalization concepts and aspirations.
</P>
<P>
It said that each country has its own rights fully to maneuver
within the framework of its sovereign powers to practice flexible
policies in following the development trend without any dictates
from outside.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government rejected the resolution passed on
Wednesday by the current session of the ILC, affirming that there
are no practices of forced labor in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
