<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reactions to Sri Lankan Rebels' New Thinking Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil Tiger rebels'
new thinking to have a independent state shared by Tamils and
Muslims received mixed reactions in the country, officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tamil United Liberation Front Leader Annadasagari told Xinhua
that rebels' latest attempt to woo the Muslims in Sri Lanka's
Eastern Province is a "good sign."
</P>
<P>
Annadasagari, who is a member of Parliament, said that "Muslims
have been pushed out from the areas and are not allowed to live
together with the Tamils in North and the East. But, now with this
change of attitude of the LTTE , both the Tamils and the Muslims
can live together."
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels, fighting a
17-year war against the government to carve out a separate Eelam
or state for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east, last
week distributed a leaflet in an attempt to woo the Muslims living
in the province.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has a population of 19 million, of which the majority
Sinhalese constitute 74 percent while Tamils and Muslims
constitute 18 and 8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE calls on Muslims to be vigilant against a campaign to
foment divisions between them and the Tamil people in the east.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE leaflet said that Muslims need not be concerned about
"the imminent war of liberation that is soon to engulf the east."
</P>
<P>
"Tamil Eelam belongs to the Muslim and Tamil people," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior member of Parliament of the Sri Lanka Muslim
Congress, who requested not to be named due to threats for his
life, brushed off the LTTE's attempt as a mere tactic.
</P>
<P>
"Muslims are not for Eelam. It is a tactic by the LTTE to woo
the Muslims before the referendum," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government reached an agreement with the main
opposition United National Party (UNP) last week that referendum
would be the means of deciding whether the currently merged North-
East Province should be merged as one province or should be
separated.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will be conducted in the Batticaloa and
Trincomalee districts where a considerable number of Muslims live.
</P>
<P>
A.H.M. Azwer, a Muslim member of Parliament in UNP, did not see
the new signals of the LTTE as very welcome to the Muslims of Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"Muslims live in the entire island peacefully. Let our future
not be jeopardized by these things," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Lead Regional Retailing Recovery: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will likely record the
highest rate of retail sales growth in Southeast Asia in the
second half of this year, the Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fuelled by the economic recovery, retail sales in Thailand are
likely to rise by 15 percent from the same period of last year to
126.5 billion baht (3.24 billion U.S. dollars), Suthichart
Chirathivat, president of the Thailand Retailers' Association, was
quoted as forecasting.
</P>
<P>
He based his forecast on talks with presidents of retailers'
associations in the region, where most consumers are continuing to
restrict their purchases because of economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the Thai economy has been improving, based on
an increase in exports and in easing of debt problems.
</P>
<P>
Retailers in the region had increased cooperation in obtaining
products. "We obtain hardware from some and supply them with
garments in return," said Suthichart, president of Thailand's
largest retailing group Central Retail Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
