<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Lags Behind Rivals in IT Economy: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's efforts to develop a
knowledge-based economy and apply new telecommunications
technologies lag behind those of other members of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), the Bangkok Post Monday quoted
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Thailand Retailers' Association on Sunday, Tarrin
said supporting development of information technology is crucial
for the country to maintain global competitiveness in the "new
economy."
</P>
<P>
"We must give priority to this issue, just as 100 years ago
when Thailand first began to lay tracks for the country's rail
network," he said, adding "Development of the Internet and
communications links will form a critical piece of the country's
infrastructure for the future."
</P>
<P>
According to the National Electronics and Computer Technology
Center, Thailand has only 16.7 computers per 1,000 people,
compared with 42.8 in Malaysia, 131.7 in South Korea and 216.8 in
Singapore. Internet usage in Thailand is also far behind that in
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said that Internet would lead to new businesses and
industries, affecting companies not only in e-commerce, but also
in financial and supply management.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has moved to set up a legal infrastructure
to support e-commerce and electronic payments. Other measures are
in place to lower telecommunications costs within the country.
</P>
<P>
As Thailand emerges from the economic crisis which began three
years ago, Tarrin said it is crucial for policy makers to look to
the future.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the government expected the economic growth this
year to be at 4.5 to five percent, compared with 4.2 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
Still, he said, the economy would require at least another year
before recovering to pre-crisis levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Head of InterAction Council Slaps NATO for Operation in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the InterAction
Council Malcolm Fraser strongly condemned here Sunday the
operation launched in Kosovo by the U.S.-led NATO last year as an
ironical scheme.
</P>
<P>
Fraser, former Australian Prime Minister, made the condemnation
at the opening ceremony of the 18th annual meeting of the
InterAction Council, an organization of former heads of state and
government.
</P>
<P>
He noted that before NATO's military intervention in Kosovo, a
Yugoslav province plagued by ethnic problems, the number of
refugees in the region was only 70,000. But it rose to 1.2 million
at the end of the war, and 90 percent of the killed were civilians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western military bloc launched an airstrike
against Yugoslavia from March to June last year, wantonly bombing
the Balkan country for 78 days and destroying countless civilian
buildings and lives.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the meeting, Vice Chairman of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference Song Jian echoed
Fraser's view on Kosovo. He pointed out that the Kosovo war NATO
launched under the excuse of "safeguarding humanism" actually
brought about the biggest catastrophe of humanism in Europe since
the end of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the end of the war has not eased ethnic conflicts
in Kosovo still tormented by prominent refugee problems and has
far from achieved peace and stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
This well proves that bombs cannot produce peace, Song said.
Any attempt to dominate the international affairs and build a
single-polar world in its own interest by any country with its
strong economic and military power would threaten the world peace
and security and trample on international norms.
</P>
<P>
Finnish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen also spoke at the opening
ceremony of the three-day meeting attended by nearly 50 former
heads of state and government and other VIPs from over 20
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
