<HEADLINE> International Trafficking Ring Smashed in Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 18 (Xinhua)-- Berlin municipal police smashed an
international cocaine trafficking ring here Sunday during a
coordinated operation with their French counterparts.
</P>
<P>
About 90 policemen made 12 arrests and seized 10 kilograms of
cocaine, worth 1 million Marks (about 0.5 million U.S. dollars),
when they stormed 18 residential houses and stores, police sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Under arrest were Lebanese, Turkish Kurds and three Germans,
two of them being women aged between 19 and 24. Several vehicles
used for transporting drugs were also confiscated during the
operation.
</P>
<P>
After the preliminary interrogation, the police have linked
the case to a public security company in Berlin, which provides
security services to big shots from Arab countries. The director
of the company, a 28-year-old Lebanese agent, is suspected to be
the hidden organizer.
</P>
<P>
The drugs, believed to have originated from South America, were
put in a suitcase and brought here from Paris by a German staff of
the company last night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
