<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woods Wins Open with Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Tiger Woods won the 100th U.S.
Open in Pebble Beach, california, on Sunday by 15 strokes in the
most lopsided triumph in major championship golf history.
</P>
<P>
Woods fired a final-round score of four-under-par 67 for a 12-
under 272 total to put a magnificent finishing touch in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Woods tied the Open mark for low total score,
broke the record for lowest score in relation to par and the mark
for widest margin of victory in the most complete rout ever seen
in major golf.
</P>
<P>
The victory brought 800,000 U.S. dollars to Woods, the all-time
leading money winner in golf.
</P>
<P>
Two-time Open champion Ernie Els of South Africa and Spain's
Miguel Angel Jimenez finished tied for faraway second at three
over par.
</P>
<P>
The previous widest margin of victory in the history of the
majors was 13 strokes, set by Tom Morris Sr. at the 1862 British
Open in Prestwick, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
In an Open championship where no other player even matched par
the tournament, Woods finished four strokes better than the
previous record for best score in relation to par.
</P>
<P>
The original mark of eight under par had been shared by Jack
Nicklaus (1980 Baltusrol), Lee Janzen (1993 Baltusrol), Hale Irwin
(1990 Medinah) and Mike Donald (1990 Medinah).
</P>
<P>
World number one Woods raised his major championship total to
three, following his 1997 Masters win and 1999 PGA Championship
triumph. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
