<HEADLINE> Australia's Wilson Wins Women's Challenge Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian Anna Wilson held on
in the final stage to win her second Women's Challenge cycling
race by 27 seconds over Lithuanian Diana Ziliute on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wilson assumed her second race lead from Ziliute after her
victory in Saturday's 10th stage of the 125,000 U.S. dollars event.
</P>
<P>
Sarah Ulmer of New Zealand finished third overall, three
minutes and 15 seconds behind in the 1,007 kilometers race
throughout the state of Idaho that began June 8 in Boise.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Jeannie Longo of France, who won three of
the first five stages but also missed three key stage breaks,
finished fourth overall, 3:16 back.
</P>
<P>
Wilson, winner of the event in 1996, held the race lead twice --
at the beginning and at the end.
</P>
<P>
She claimed the first stage but lost the lead the following day
to Ziliute. Wilson regained the lead Saturday when she, American
teammate Dede Demet Barry and three others built a margin in the
criterium that eventually allowed the group to lap the field.
</P>
<P>
American Karen Kurreck outsprinted five other cyclists to win
the 11th and final stage, 6:52 behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
Margaret Hemsley of Australia was second and American Andrea
Ratkovic third as the leading group of six was given the same
finishing time, 57 seconds ahead of the main field.
</P>
<P>
Only 81 of the starting field of 116 finished the 17th annual
Women's Challenge, the world's most lucrative women's cycling
event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
