<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Chinese scientists said that they have already drawn a
genetic linkage map of common carp, making it possible for
fostering new species of carp with some good characters.
</P>
<P>
According to the research, carp's ability of cold resistance
rely on a kind of gene. Scientists have successfully got six pairs
of gene markers, which can enable ordinary carp to resist cold
effectively. Experts believe that this is the first achievement in
the circle in the world.
</P>
<P>
-- Experts with the consultant group of World Bank said after a
recent examination that construction on the Xiaolangdi Water
Control Project, a key project to harness the sand silting of the
Yellow River's bed, has brought no damage to the surrounding
environment since it started six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Harvey F. Ludwig, chief expert of the group, said tests by the
experts of World Bank show that all the index of the project have
reached the world standard in terms of environmental protection.
It is clear that authority's awareness and measures to protect
environment have been well carried out during the construction
work, he said.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin told scores of international
leaders and businesspeople who are here to attend the 21st Century
Forum --2000 Conference, which begins on Wednesday, that China
wants to hear the opinions of world leaders on economic
globalization at the forum to expand common ground and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The forum, sponsored by the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), runs until
Friday. The theme of the forum is "economic globalization -- Asia
and China."
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said that he hopes all young
people, both Chinese and foreign, and all scientists and scholars
around the world will make the best use of the Internet, but
should guard against negative impacts of the net.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji will pay an official visit to six
European countries and the headquarters of the European Union (EU)
between June 27 and July 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- China will further open up its financial institutions in the
next few years, creating fresh opportunities for foreign investors,
said central bank governor Dai Xianglong.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the "21st Century Forum -- Conference 2000", Dai,
governor of the People's Bank of China, said that five years after
China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO), foreign
companies and foreign banks in China will enjoy "national
treatment".
</P>
<P>
Chinese business executives at the economic forum said that
improving the international competitive edge is the only way Chine
's big businesses and conglomerates can survive economic
globalization and prosper.
</P>
<P>
With China's entry into the WTO pending and the pace of
economic globalization increasing, some Chinese business
executives that they are making headway in meeting challenges
facing the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
-- China's huge energy project to pipe gas from west to east,
expected to cost as much as the Three Gorges Project, will be
launched in early 2001 and should end by 2003.
</P>
<P>
A major gas pipeline with total length of 4,200 kilometers will
be built with initial 120-billion yuan (about 14 billion US
dollars) investment for the project, according to Huang Yicheng,
chairman of the executive council of the China Energy Research
Society (CERS).
</P>
<P>
-- China will start a five-year sand-control project on the
outskirts of the capital to improve the environment, the State
Forestry Administration announced.
</P>
<P>
As a part of a national sand control programs, the project
involves 116 counties in Beijing, Tianjin, Hebei Province, the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and Shaanxi Province, covering an
area of some 464,000 square km.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese scientists working in the Northwest University of
Agriculture and Forestry Science and Technology have cloned the
first live goat from adult body cells in the world, Zhang Yong,
announced a professor with the university.
</P>
<P>
The baby goat, named "Yuanyuan", 36-cm long, 30-cm tall and
weighting 2.8 kgs, was cloned using ear cells of an adult goat,
said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
However, it died of breathing failure caused by defects in lung
development early Sunday morning after living 36 hours and three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
-- Four firms have formed China's largest software company
Zhongguancun Software Group with a total investment of one billion
yuan (about 120.7 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
