<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Online Payment In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- China will pilot a Certificate
Authority Center (CAC) for online payment by the end of this month
for trial operation.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC) and 13 commercial banks in
the country will join hands in establishing the Center, said Chen
Jing, section chief of PBOC at an international forum on E-
business recently in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The Center will offer solutions to the security of online
settlements by granting security certificates to online traders.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that unsafe online payment severely restricts the
development of E-commerce in China.
</P>
<P>
The Third International e-business Forum was sponsored by the
Tianjin Municipal People's Government, the U.S. Cyber Century
Forum and other organizations. The two-day event discussed the
future of E-business, international cooperation, and E-business
solutions for small and medium companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Ethnic Gene Banks Established in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Six ethnic gene banks have been
established in the Harbin Medical Sciences University in northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The genes of six ethnic minority groups including the Mongolian
and the Xibo are currently frozen in liquefied nitrogen at minus
273 degrees Celsius, awaiting for deciphering.
</P>
<P>
The gene banks are set up to preserve genes of the ethnic
minority groups so that scientists may have the opportunity to get
to know the secrets behind some special anti-disease genes in such
ethnic groups and find a cure for such diseases someday, said Li
Pu, a professor on genetics in the university.
</P>
<P>
Such banks are necessary since those special genes of Chinese
ethnic minority groups are gradually disappearing as more and more
most ethnic minority people marry into other ethnic groups, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
"Once needed for research, the original genes could be
reactivated and duplicated," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li added that his university also plans to provide 50 sample
cells for an international gene bank so that it might purchase
sample cells of foreign ethnic groups someday for research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
