<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030, June 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Bashar al-Assad, the son of the late Syrian
president Hafez al-Assad, on Sunday was appointed leader of
Syria's ruling Baath party which is holding its ninth congress.
</P>
<P>
Bashar is expected to be elected secretary-general of the party
at the end of the congress, which is due to end Wednesday, the
official SANA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Observers said it is almost certain that the 1,021 delegates
attending the congress are to give approval to Bashar's
appointment. (Syria-Bashar-Party Leader)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said here Sunday
that U.N. peacekeeping forces should be immediately deployed in an
effort to bolster a peace deal signed on Sunday between Ethiopia
and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The concerned parties should try to implement the peace
agreement quickly, Annan said of the accord that the two countries
clinched in Algiers, capital of Algeria, earlier to end their two-
year border war. (Egypt-Annan-Peacekeepers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein on Sunday named
prominent legislator Ali Abu Ragheb as prime minister to succeed
Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh, but commended the latter for his 15 months of
service as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Ragheb is expected to be sworn in as prime minister before the
king in the coming days, most probably on Monday, informed sources
said. (Jordan-King-PM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council on Sunday
endorsed the conclusion by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that
Israel had withdrawn its forces from southern Lebanon in
accordance with resolution 425 of 1978.
</P>
<P>
The move came after two days of Marathon negotiations among the
15-member Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement which was read in an open, formal
meeting by Council President for the current month, Jean-David
Levitte of France, the Security Council also acknowledged that
there may have been some violations of the border, a move seen
widely here as an apparent bid to ease Russia's concern. (UN-
Israel-Lebanon-Withdrawn)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Resisting pressure from the United States, Lebanese
President Emile Lahoud on Sunday again refused to approve that
Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon is complete.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese National News Agency reported Lahoud said in a
statement released Sunday that "Lebanon will not lose its hard-
earned victory with resistance and sacrifice after just several
hours of talking."
</P>
<P>
Lahoud made the statement after U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright made intensified efforts earlier in the day to
try to convince Lebanon to accept a U.N. Security Council
statement that could indicate Israel has completed its 22-year
occupation of south Lebanon. (Lebanon-UN-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Visiting European Union (EU) Middle East peace envoy
Mieguel Muratinos on Sunday expressed optimism over the Middle
East peace process, saying he expects breakthroughs in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference in Amman, Muratinos said he believes the
Middle East is more closer than ever to a solution to the decades-
old Arab-Israeli conflicts.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not mention the fact the Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators failed to make substantial progress in
their final status talks after their resumption earlier this month
in Washington, and the Syrian-Israeli talks remains deadlocked
since they broke off in January. (Jordan-EEU Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain's police and army in Northern Ireland came
under attack from nationalist rioters protesting at an Orange
Order Parade in Lurgan in County Armagh on Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Police said about 30 petrol bombs, as well as ball bearings and
golf balls were thrown at the security forces, the BBC reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Three police officers and one soldier were slightly injured in
the violence and one man was arrested.
</P>
<P>
Police said three people were hit by baton rounds during the
clashes which lasted for about an hour. (Britain-Northern Ireland-
Riot)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said here Sunday
that it is the U.N. that has the authority to verify the Lebanese-
Israeli border, not the two parties involved.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remark during a news conference with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa following their talks, in which they
discussed the Middle East peace process and the situation in
Lebanon, and other Mideast issues.
</P>
<P>
Verification of Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon and
certification of the move is the job of the U.N., not either party,
Annan said. (UN-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A classified report by a Defense Department-
appointed panel of experts has raised concerns about the speed of
U.S. plans to deploy a national missile defense(NMD) system by
2005, including doubts whether interceptors can yet distinguish
between armed warheads and decoys, The Washington Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The report was given to Defense Secretary William Cohen last
week by an independent panel headed by retired General Larry Welch,
former Air Force chief of staff, the newspaper said in Sunday
editions.
</P>
<P>
It questioned the current maturity of the technology, raising
concerns about the problem of dummy decoys launched with attacking
missiles, and about pressure from the U.S. Congress for fast-track
2005 deployment of a yet-unproved system. (US-Pentagon-Missile
Plan) 
</P>
</TEXT>
