<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Japanese PM Takeshita Dies at 76 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Former Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita died of respiratory failure at 00:53 local time
Monday (1553 GMT Sunday) at a Tokyo hospital, Kyodo News reported.
He was 76.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita, a member of the House of Representatives for the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), served as Japan's prime
minister from 1987 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
A native of Shimane Prefecture, western Japan, Takeshita had
been elected to the House of Representatives 14 times.
</P>
<P>
The English-teacher-turned-politician began his political
career as a member of the Shimane prefectural assembly in 1951 at
the age of 27. In 1958, he debuted in national politics at 34,
winning a seat in the lower house as an LDP member.
</P>
<P>
He became a political heavyweight in 1964, when he was chosen
deputy chief cabinet secretary in the first cabinet of late Prime
Minister Eisaku Sato.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita continued to exert a strong influence on Japanese
politics long after he resigned as Japanese prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Takeshita had been hospitalized since early April last year
with spondylitis.
</P>
<P>
Following the sudden hospitalization of the late Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi on April 2, Takeshita said on May 1 in a
tape-recorded message that he would not seek reelection in the
upcoming general election for the lower house and retire from
politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
