<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Discourages dumping Bone Ashes in River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The government of this
municipality in southwest China has appealed to its citizens not
to dump bone ash into the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
"Bone ash pollutes the river," said Zeng Guangming, a civil
affairs official with the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that although dumping of bone ash into the sea or
rivers is a form of burial advocated by the central government to
save wasting arable land, it is not suitable in Chongqing, which
is at the lower end of the 600-km-long Three Gorges Reservoir,
which is now under construction.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir will store water and generate electricity by the
year 2003, when the speed of the current will slow down, making it
easier for pollutants to stagnate in the world's third-largest
river.
</P>
<P>
The official said that it should be quite satisfactory to bury
bone ash under trees or place urns in towers.
</P>
<P>
He urged Chongqing citizens to follow the example of the city
of Harbin in northeast China, where a number of people have
sprayed bone ash of their deceased relatives over flower beds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Hits Zhejiang Fisheries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Infestation of red tide over the
past few weeks has dealt a heavy blow to the fisheries industry in
east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Dead fish, shrimps, crabs and clams can be seen all along the
coast, and the economic losses are said to be in the millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the East China Sea Monitoring Center affiliated
with the State Oceanic Administration said that the scale of the
red tide this year has been unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
The red tide, which manifested itself from May 3, was formed by
Prorocentrum dentatum and Prorocentrum minimum, both poisonous
substances.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries departments in the province have urged people to
control the flow of sea water to breeding ponds.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has traditionally been vulnerable to red tides,
oceanographers said. In 1993 and 1997, the province reported 132
red tide sightings, ranking first in all coast provinces of China.
</P>
<P>
A 1993 red tide caused an economic loss of 385 million yuan (
about 45 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Researchers have appealed to the government to tighten
monitoring of red tides using both boats and satellite systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
