<HEADLINE> Survey: Split Up Shows No Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The order for the breakup of the
Microsoft by a United States federal court last week had little
impact on Chinese computer users' choices for hardware and
software, a survey conducted by an independent market researcher
in Beijing has indicated.
</P>
<P>
And many of those surveyed believed splitting up the giant
software manufacturer would be conducive to creating a fair market
competitive environment, today's China Daily quoted a report by
the Beijing Consumer Research Co. as saying.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on inquiries from 109 persons in China's
information technology industry, found that 56 percent favored US
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's order to split Microsoft
into two companies.
</P>
<P>
Only one-fifth of those surveyed opposed the breakup, while the
rest took a wait and see attitude.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-six percent of the respondents said that Microsoft had
monopolistic power in the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a high-ranking official from Microsoft China said
that the judicial ruling will not produce any impact on its
Chinese business in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
