<HEADLINE> Popov Misses World Record in 100m Freestyle at Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia's world and Olympic champion
Alexander Popov narrowly missed breaking a second world record in
two days at the national swimming championships here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Popov, who set the 50 meters freestyle world record of 21.64
seconds on Friday, clocked 48.27 in his 100m freestyle semi-final
heat, missing his own world mark of 48.21 set at the 1994 world
championships in Rome. Popov's performance showed he is close to
his top form in time for his third Olympics, in Sydney in
September.
</P>
<P>
But he stopped short of predicting he would break the 100m
record in Monday's final.
</P>
<P>
Popov won the 50m and 100m freestyle events at both the 1992
and 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Roman Sludnov, who on Friday won the 100m breaststroke final
while setting a world record, added the 200m title with a time of
two minutes 12.26 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Dual 1996 Olympic butterfly champion Denis Pankratov had his
200m butterfly world record of 1:55.22 broken on Saturday by
American Tom Malchow who lowered it by four hundredths of a second
in Charlotte, North Carolina. And Pankratov was beaten into
second place by Anatoly Polyakov in the 200m final. Polyakov won
the race in 1:57.31, beating Pankratov by a full second.
</P>
<P>
Pankratov won both the 100m and 200m at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
