<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Arrives in Britain for Second Bout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Former world heavyweight boxing
champion Mike Tyson arrived in London for his bout against fellow
American Lou Savarese in Scotland next week.
</P>
<P>
Wearing a black and white open necked shirt and dark trousers,
Tyson arrived on a Concorde flight from New York and had his
documents checked onboard the plane by immigration officials. A
car met him on the tarmac and took him to London, a Reuters report
said.
</P>
<P>
Tyson made no comment to reporters.
</P>
<P>
Under British immigration rules, anyone who has been convicted
of an offence that carries a jail sentence of more than 12 months
is refused entry unless there are "strong compassionate or
exceptional reasons" for the visit.
</P>
<P>
Tyson served three years in jail for rape.
</P>
<P>
The boxer was supposed to arrive in Britain on Wednesday but
delayed his departure to attend the funeral of a friend in New
York. He will stay in London for two days before moving north to
Scotland next Wednesday. He fights Savarese in Hampden Park
stadium, Glasgow, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's low-key arrival was in marked contrast to the last time
he came to Britain earlier this year. On that occasion he was the
center of a scrum of media, fans and police.
</P>
<P>
"In the interest of public safety it was decided that we didn't
want a repeat of the scenes when he arrived earlier this year. So
both the police and airport authorities decided that he should be
driven straight from his plane," an airport official said.
</P>
<P>
The decision by police and officials meant that Tyson also
missed the delays that are hindering other travellers after a
computer glitch caused chaos on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In January, Tyson beat local boxer Julius Francis in four
minutes in front of a packed arena in Manchester. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Has Authority in Verifying Lebanese-Israeli Border: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
said here Sunday that it is the U.N. that has the authority to
verify the Lebanese-Israeli border, not the two parties involved.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remark during a news conference with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa following their talks, in which they
discussed the Middle East peace process and the situation in
Lebanon, and other Mideast issues.
</P>
<P>
Verification of Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon and
certification of the move is the job of the U.N., not either party,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said on Friday that Israel's May 24 withdrawal from south
Lebanon was complete under the U.N. Security Council Resolution
425. Lebanon, meanwhile, disputed the confirmation, insisting that
the Jewish state still occupies Lebanon in several areas.
</P>
<P>
Annan, however, played down the disagreement between the U.N.
and Lebanon, saying he would not describe it as a dispute. He
expressed hope that it was only a hiccup that will soon be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he had talked to Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss
before meeting Annan, and Cairo took Lebanon's position seriously.
</P>
<P>
But he voiced confidence that things will be further clarified
after Annan flies to Beirut on Monday and meets with Lebanon's
president, prime minister and senior officials.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the outcome would be very positive," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan came to Egypt from Iran, the first leg of his ongoing
Mideast tour. After Lebanon, he will also travel to Jordan, Syria,
Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Tops Group C after Winning over Norway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Savo Milosevic scored his third
goal of Euro 2000 on Sunday in Liege, Belgium as Yugoslavia
defeated Norway 1-0 to top Group C.
</P>
<P>
It was Yugoslavia's first victory at the European championship
in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic scored in the seventh minute, standing with his back
to goal and deflecting a low freekick from Ljubinko Drulovic into
the corner of the net.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav substitute Mateja Kezman was sent off a minute from
coming on for a late tackle on Erik Mykland in the 88th minute.
But even with a man down, Yugoslavia survived a Norwegian
challenge.
</P>
<P>
The win over the early group leaders, coupled with Spain's 2-1
defeat of Slovenia, left Yugoslavia top on four points with one
match against Spain to come.
</P>
<P>
Spain and Norway each has three, Slovenia one.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia, making five changes to their starting line-up,
looked a totally different side to the toothless team that was 3-0
down to Slovenia in the first 60 minutes of its opening match
before drawing 3-3.
</P>
<P>
With defender Sinisa Mihajlovic suspended after being sent off
against Slovenia, Yugoslavia revamped its highly suspect defence
with only fullback Miroslav Djukic retaining his place.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, who came on as a second-half substitute against
Slovenia to score two goals, started and looked immediately lively
in the area.
</P>
<P>
He was back on the scoreseheet in the eighth minute with the
slightest of deflections off a Vladimir Jugovic free kick on the
right near the edge of the area.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia could have had more goals, with goalkeeper Thomas
Myhre tipping Predrag Mijatovic's shot over the bar and Milosevic
denied his second by Bjorn Otto Bragstad when his 17th minute shot
was blocked.
</P>
<P>
Norway, without injured captain Henning Berg, left Chelsea
striker Tore Andre Flo as its main striker and he always looked
dangerous without finding that final scoring touch that has eluded
him since October.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after half-time, Vladimir Jugovic came close with
a thunderous shot which was well saved and Mijatovic almost added
a second in the 50th minute. At this stage, it was Myhre who kept
Norway in touch.
</P>
<P>
Then Norway could have equalized once again when Flo, noticing
that Kralj is way out from his goal, broke away through the middle
but Djukic deflected the ball away from his foot in the last
moment.
</P>
<P>
Gradually however, the game degenerated into an ill-tempered
affair with crunching tackles and clashes of the head. Yellow
cards came flying, with six bookings in total.
</P>
<P>
Norway finally started relying on its superior physical
conditioning to launch a final onslaught. Substitute John Carew
came closest in the 90th minute but his tap past Kralj went just
wide.
</P>
<P>
"It was a fantastic victory, my players died on the pitch,
they fought all the way," Yugoslavia's coach Vujadin Boskov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
