<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England FA Concerned by UEFA Procedure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June (Xinhua) -- England's Football Association said
on Sunday it had concerns about how UEFA made its decision to warn
England it might be kicked out of Euro 2000 if hooliganism
continued, according to Spa, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Most of the fans who caused the trouble in Belgium over the
past two days were "unknown" to the authorities, a senior FA
official said.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly we have significant concerns about the way events
today have unfolded," David Davies said.
</P>
<P>
No senior FA official was asked to attend the UEFA meeting,
Davies said. The FA's security adviser did attend the meeting but
he was asked no questions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The question of how far the FA is responsible for so-called
fans ... is a matter we will seek to discuss at an urgent meeting
we will be requesting with (UEFA chief executive) Gert Aigner
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
"The vast majority of those causing problems were not
previously known to the authorities," said Davies.
</P>
<P>
Earlier UEFA threatened to kick England out of Euro 2000 on
Sunday following two days of street violence by hooligans in
Belgium and slammed the British government for failing to stop
them travelling abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statement of England FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- After UEFA's threat to throw
England out of Euro 2000 if its fans misbehave again, the Football
Association on Sunday issued a statement, read at a news
conference by executive director David Davies:
</P>
<P>
"The FA takes today's statement by UEFA very seriously indeed.
</P>
<P>
"More than anything else, we want to be part of a safe and
secure festival of football, similar to Euro 96 in England.
</P>
<P>
"Let us be absolutely clear straight away. We condemn utterly
and without reservation the actions of thugs and criminals we have
seen on our television sets, and some of you have seen in person,
in Brussels and in Charleroi.
</P>
<P>
"We know the British government shares in that condemnation.
Their response to today's statement by UEFA is for them.
</P>
<P>
"But as far as the FA is concerned, it is public knowledge
that we called for emergency legislation to remove passports from
potential troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
"We are bound to point out then that all the evidence
available suggests that the vast majority of those causing trouble
in Belgium this weekend were not previously known to the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
"The FA, as you know, has worked tirelessly to prepare for
this tournament. We have made all our resources available to our
opposite numbers in Belgium and Holland.
</P>
<P>
"We have restricted the sale of tickets to members of the
England Members' Club, all of whom are subject to official vetting.
They have played, as I'm sure you will agree, a significant part
in creating the excellent atmosphere in the stadia both in
Charleroi and Eindhoven.
</P>
<P>
"Kevin Keegan, our coach, has appealed, before we came here to
Belgium, for all supporters to recognize their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"His job tonight and tomorrow is to prepare the national team
for an absolutely crucial game for our country.
</P>
<P>
"But we repeat his appeal, that appeal, tonight, on behalf of
Kevin, on behalf of every single player who is here in Spa, and
particularly on behalf of English football.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly though, we have significant concerns about the way
today's events have unfolded.
</P>
<P>
"Neither our chairman, nor our chief executive, nor any other
senior FA employee attended today's UEFA meeting. Our security
adviser, Sir Brian Hayes, was invited to make a very brief
statement late in the proceedings but had no other input to the
discussion.
</P>
<P>
"He was asked no questions and was asked to leave before a
media statement was issued just minutes later.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of how far a football association is responsible
for so-called fans well away from any stadium _ something UEFA has
always rejected in the past _ is a matter that we will seek to
discuss at the urgent meeting we will be requesting with Gerhard
Aigner, the chief executive of UEFA, tomorrow."  
</P>
</TEXT>
