<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Appeals Court Procedural Ruling Favors Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The federal appeals court here
Monday made a ruling in favor of Microsoft Corp. by rejecting a
request by the U.S. government that it stay out of the huge
antitrust case against the giant software maker.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Court of Appeals for Washington, D.C., in a second
victory for Microsoft, turned down a Justice Department motion to
summarily dismiss the company's requested stay of a federal judge'
s June 7 order to break it into two companies and restrict its
business practices.
</P>
<P>
The department had sought to have the appellate court bypassed
in the appeals process following U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's earlier this month. The department wants the
case sent directly to the Supreme Court for review.
</P>
<P>
The decision Monday thwarting that attempt was the latest in a
series of legal skirmishes between Microsoft and the government in
the wake of Jackson's order that Microsoft be split in two as a
remedy for violating antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
The appeals court Monday said the Justice Department now had 10
days to respond to its ruling on the stay request, after which
Microsoft would have seven days to reply.
</P>
<P>
But it cautioned that if Judge Jackson agreed to a government
request and sent the entire case directly to the U.S. Supreme
Court, the proposed schedule "would be automatically suspended."
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department issued a statement applauding that part
of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
"We're very pleased with the court's ruling that it would stay
further proceedings if the district court certifies the case for
direct appeal to the Supreme Court," said department spokeswoman
Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
Jackson postponed his split of Microsoft from taking effect
until the case makes its way through the appeals process. However,
the restrictions he ordered on company business practices would
start taking effect on September 5.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Microsoft asked the appellate court for a stay after
Jackson deferred a decision on a stay. On Thursday, Microsoft
filed a brief in the appellate court arguing that it was not
required to wait for Jackson's ruling.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the department told the federal appeals court that
Microsoft violated federal rules of procedure by asking it to stay
antitrust penalties before the trial judge ruled on the same
request.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department has requested that Jackson send the case
directly to the Supreme Court, bypassing the appellate court,
which has reversed Jackson's decisions regarding Microsoft in the
past. The past record of the appellate court toward Microsoft is
the reason the software-maker maneuvered to get the case heard by
that court.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said Monday it expects slower growth in sales and
operating margins in its 2000 fiscal year, partially as the result
of its legal battles with the government.
</P>
<P>
The company, in a document filed with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission, also cited stepped-up competition in its
traditional sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
