<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS Defense Ministers Move to Expand Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) defense ministers decided here Monday to strengthen
their nations' military cooperation by developing a unified air
defense system.
</P>
<P>
The CIS states unanimously agreed to enhance the commonwealth's
inner military cooperation, which is of strategic character,
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told a news conference
after a session of the Council of Defense Ministers of the CIS
here.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministers discussed the program on the development
of the military cooperation in the framework of the CIS by 2005
and agreed to unite their forces to cover "the arc of instability"
from the Pamir to the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
The joint actions will be aimed at preventing weapons, drugs
and bandit groups from penetrating CIS countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's session, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov urged
CIS countries to pool their efforts to consolidate international
stability.
</P>
<P>
"Our coordinated actions have a special significance against
the background of a mounting new global challenge -- the danger of
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and their means of
delivery," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The most topical task today is to strengthen international
strategic stability, the cornerstone of which is the 1972 Anti-
Ballistic-Missile treaty," Ivanov said. "This is the only
efficient way to counteract the peril of nuclear missile
proliferation without destroying the whole system of disarmament
accords."
</P>
<P>
"Russia has proposed a constructive alternative to the
unilateral undermining of the ABM treaty: establishing a European
system of non-strategic missile defense," he said, urging CIS
states to support this program.
</P>
<P>
He also called on CIS countries to jointly fight against
increasing threats of "various extremist forces and groups" and "
international terrorism." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
