<HEADLINE> Panama, Costa Rica Reach Common Steps regarding Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Over 50 ways for vehicular passage
may be used together by Costa Rican and Panamanian authorities
without any control at all, an official source announced here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Armando Fuentes, official of Panama's Fiscal Office, said both
countries arrived at this accord at a meeting at the country's
border with Costa Rica last week.
</P>
<P>
At the encounter, it was also agreed to strengthen vigilance
along Canoa pass and other passes for taking out or bringing
illegally cars in either through Panamanian land toward Costa Rica
or from the latter toward Panamanian land.
</P>
<P>
Present at this event were customs' officials and police
officers from both countries and General Attorney of Panama Carlos
Arias.
</P>
<P>
Recently, both countries have managed to define the placement
of boundary posts at borders they share for over 300 kilometers,
as both nations only count with three border control posts.
</P>
<P>
Police of both countries are patrolling at the borders to
survey matters related with international traffic of drugs and
arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Witness Talks of Detonation in Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, June 19 (Xinhua) -- An electronics
manufacturer on Monday admitted in court that his company had
fitted out briefcases with the gadgets for detonating bombs.
</P>
<P>
Edwin Bollier, owner of the Geneva-based electronics
manufacturer MEBO AG, told Scottish judges that his company had
converted Swiss Telekom and Motorola pagers into radio-controlled
detonators and secured them into the suitcases prepared to contain
bombs.
</P>
<P>
The man is a critical witness for prosecutors hoping to link
the two Libyan defendants to the mid-air bombing of the Pan Am
Flight 103 on December 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah are
accused of conspiracy for murder and breach of international
aircraft safety law.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution alleged that the two Libyan defendants had"
ordered and attempted to obtain" 40 electronic timers from MEBO AG
from November 20 to December 20, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Investigators found a piece of circuit board from one timer in
the aircraft wreckage which they believed was made by Bollier's
company.
</P>
<P>
Bollier spoke for less than an hour before the court was
adjourned. His testimony continues on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The defense team, however, sharply cross-examined Irwin Meyer,
MEBO's co-owner who was accused of lying, forging documents,
fabricating evidence and blackmailing the Libyan government. Meyer
denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
Meyer denied a defense claim that MEBO AG had offered to cover
for Libya by saying it had supplied electronic timers to an
extremist group in Beirut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000619.0363 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Becomes Mexico's Main Importer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela became the main
destination of Mexican products in Latin America in the year 2000
's first three-monthly period, said the National Bank of Foreign
Trade (Bancomext) Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's sales to Venezuela from January to March amounted to
110.6 million dollars, far above those of Brazil and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, trade between Mexico and Venezuela reached 733.3
million dollars, with a balance favoring the northern country for
139.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and Colombia have held with Colombia, in force since
1995, the Free Trade Agreement (TLC) of the Group of Three (G-3).
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's purchases in the year 2000's first three monthly-
period came to 113.1 million dollars, an increase of 30.6 percent
over 1999's same period, for a surplus of 2.5 million dollars in
favor of the South American country.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela is registering a noteworthy increase in acquiring
Mexican agro-products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
