<HEADLINE> Ghana, Nigeria to Lead Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Ghana and Nigeria vowed on Monday to
move towards integration even without the full endorsement of
other members of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
After 25 years of existence, ECOWAS should be running instead
of crawling, especially in the face of increasing globalization
and the challenges associated with it, Ghana News Agency quoted
high-ranking Ghanaian and Nigerian officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's trade and industry minister Dan Abodakpi and his
Nigerian counterpart Mustafa Bello made the remarks at the opening
of a meeting of trade ministers from the ECOWAS nations held in
the Ghanaian capital Accra on the "Trade Liberalization Scheme."
</P>
<P>
The meeting is a follow-up to the fast-track approach adopted
by Ghana and Nigeria at the last ECOWAS summit last December in
Lome, Togo, on the accelerated implementation of strategies for
attainment of a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
Abodakpi said globalization is about securing larger markets,
adding that regional integration is the most viable way to address
the requirements of globalization and its challenges.
</P>
<P>
Bello said Ghana and Nigeria could not wait if the other
countries in the region were not ready to move on, hence the fast
track approach.
</P>
<P>
"If the other countries are not ready, we will go on with the
integration process. There is no reason to postpone things
anymore," he explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
