<HEADLINE> D.R.Congo Says Its Allies Will Pull Out Troops As Asked by U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The foreign minister of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R.Congo), Yerodia Abdoulaye
Ndombasi, said here Monday that the three African countries which
support the D.R.Congo government will pull out their troops as has
been asked by the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council asked last Friday Angola, Namibia and
Zimbabwe, which support the D.R. Congo government, and Uganda and
Rwanda, which support the rebels of the D.R. Congo, to pull out
without delay their troops from the D.R.Congo.
</P>
<P>
Ndombasi arrived here Sunday after attending the session of the
U.N. Security Council in New York last Friday, during which the
council members adopted Resolution 1304 urging the withdrawal of
all foreign troops from Congo.
</P>
<P>
The resolution first asked Uganda and Rwanda to pull out troops,
while demanding the three other countries follow suit in each step
of the process.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops have recently fought with each other
in the city of Kisangani in the eastern D.R. Congo, killing at
least 160 civilians and wounding hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the D.R. Congo embassy here,
Ndombasi said that the U.N. Security Council resolution has "
finger-pointed the aggressors -- Rwanda and Uganda." 
</P>
</TEXT>
