<HEADLINE> U.S. Officially Drops Term "Rogue State" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department said
Monday that it has stricken the term "rogue states" from its
official lexicon and replaced it with the more benign "states of
concern."
</P>
<P>
The term "rogue states" used to be applied by the U.S. State
Department to nations on its list of countries that sponsor "
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Richard Boucher explained that the change was made
because of a "certain evolution" among some countries in the "
rogue state" category.
</P>
<P>
"Some places that were described that way have embarked upon
more democratic internal life," Boucher said. "Others have been
willing to address some of the issues that are of primary concern
to the United States."
</P>
<P>
He said the term had actually been dropped some time ago
without announcement. Just as there was no official list of rogue
states, there is none for states of concern, either.
</P>
<P>
Boucher stressed that the change in terminology does not
necessarily mean a change in policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
